\toc1 The Gospel According to John
\mt2 The Gospel According to
\mt1 JOHN
\c 1
\ms1 Prologue
\m 
\v 1 \w In|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* beginning \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Word|strong="G3056"\w*,\f + \fr 1:1 \ft In the beginning (of this world, or perhaps this universe) He already existed. But why the ‘word’? If we take the word as the basic unit of verbal communication, and even representing that communication, then we have an important figure. Jehovah the Son in human form becomes the ultimate communication of God to the human race.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Word|strong="G3056"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w with|strong="G1722"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*,\f + \fr 1:1 \ft The idea seems to be that He was face to face with God (the Father), in His presence. Actually, the Text has “the God”—since the Greeks had any number of gods, the New Testament writers usually refer to Jehovah as \nd the\nd* God. In verse 2 the Text also has “the God”.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Word|strong="G3056"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \bd \w God|strong="G2316"\w*\bd*.\f + \fr 1:1 \ft The New World Translation (of the JWs) renders “a god”. They defend their choice because the noun ‘God’ occurs without the definite article, and the absence of the article in Greek has the effect of the indefinite article in English—hence ‘a god’. However, another frequent use of the absence of the definite article (in Greek) is to emphasize the quality inherent in the noun—in this case ‘\bd God\bd*’. Grammatically, the construction is ambiguous, so those who wish to deny the deity of Christ will naturally translate ‘a god’. Since John will himself make perfectly clear that Christ is very God, we take it that he is here emphasizing that inherent quality. A faithful translator will attempt to reflect the meaning intended by the author, so I would say that the New World Translation is not faithful here, since John will repeatedly make clear that Jesus is God. But there is a further consideration. If John had used the definite article we would have an equation (in Greek)—the Word = the God—which would do away with the Trinity. So John could not write ‘the God’; he will quote Christ Himself making very clear that the Father and the Son are distinct persons.\f*
\v 2 \w He|strong="G3778"\w* Himself \w existed|strong="G1510"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* beginning \w with|strong="G1722"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*.
\v 3 \w All|strong="G3956"\w* \w things|strong="G3956"\w* \w came|strong="G1096"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w be|strong="G1096"\w* \w by|strong="G1223"\w* \w Him|strong="G3739"\w*; \w that|strong="G3739"\w* \w is|strong="G3739"\w*, \w apart|strong="G5565"\w* \w from|strong="G2532"\w* \w Him|strong="G3739"\w* \w not|strong="G3761"\w* \w even|strong="G2532"\w* \w one|strong="G1520"\w* \w thing|strong="G1520"\w* \w that|strong="G3739"\w* \w has|strong="G3739"\w* \w come|strong="G1096"\w* \w into|strong="G1096"\w* \w being|strong="G1096"\w* \w came|strong="G1096"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w be|strong="G1096"\w*.\f + \fr 1:3 \ft This passage, along with Hebrews 1:10 and Colossians 1:16, makes clear that although the Trinity was doubtless involved in the creation of this planet it was Jehovah the Son who was the primary agent.\f*
\v 4 \w In|strong="G1722"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \nd \w life|strong="G2222"\w*\nd*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Life|strong="G2222"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Light|strong="G5457"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* mankind.\f + \fr 1:4 \ft In what sense can ‘the life’ be ‘the light’? In John 8:12 the Lord said, “I am the Light of the world. He who follows me will \nd not\nd* walk in the darkness but will have the Light of the Life.” Only as we participate in the Life that Christ offers do we have access to the Light. Without His Life we walk in the darkness.\f*
\v 5 \w Now|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Light|strong="G5457"\w* \w shines|strong="G5316"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w darkness|strong="G4653"\w*,\f + \fr 1:5 \ft The word here translated ‘darkness’, and another closely related word, are frequently used of both physical and moral/spiritual darkness. The latter is associated with Satan's kingdom, in fact characterizes it, while the light characterizes Christ's kingdom. Presumably the “darkness” here is moral/spiritual—Satan's kingdom.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w darkness|strong="G4653"\w* \w has|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* overcome \w it|strong="G2532"\w*.\f + \fr 1:5 \ft To this day: in Matthew 5:14 Jesus said to His disciples, “You are the light of the world”—as long as there are followers of Jesus here, there is moral/spiritual light in the world.\f*
\s1 John—a witness to the Light
\p 
\v 6 \w There|strong="G1096"\w* \w was|strong="G1096"\w* \w a|strong="G1096"\w* \w man|strong="G2316"\w*, \w sent|strong="G2316"\w* \w from|strong="G3844"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*, whose \w name|strong="G3686"\w* \w was|strong="G1096"\w* \w John|strong="G2491"\w*.
\v 7 \w This|strong="G3778"\w* \w man|strong="G3778"\w* \w came|strong="G2064"\w* \w as|strong="G1519"\w* \w a|strong="G1519"\w* \w witness|strong="G3140"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w testify|strong="G3140"\w* \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w Light|strong="G5457"\w*, \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w might|strong="G3778"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w* \w through|strong="G1223"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*.
\v 8 \w He|strong="G3588"\w* \w himself|strong="G1565"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w Light|strong="G5457"\w* \w but|strong="G3588"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w testify|strong="G3140"\w* \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w Light|strong="G5457"\w*—
\v 9 \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w true|strong="G3588"\w* \w Light|strong="G5457"\w* \w which|strong="G3739"\w* \w illumines|strong="G5461"\w* \w everyone|strong="G3956"\w* \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w comes|strong="G2064"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w world|strong="G2889"\w*.\f + \fr 1:9 \ft In what sense can we say that everyone is “illumined” since we are all born with an inclination to sin, and most people die lost? Perhaps the answer lies in Romans 1:19-20. One of the expressions of the Life is the material creation that surrounds us—everyone has the light of the creation; there must be an incredibly intelligent and powerful Cause, and since we are persons He must be more so. We also believe that each human being is born with a conscience.\f*
\v 10 \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w world|strong="G2889"\w*, \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w world|strong="G2889"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w came|strong="G1096"\w* \w into|strong="G1722"\w* \w being|strong="G1510"\w* \w by|strong="G1223"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, \w yet|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w world|strong="G2889"\w* \w did|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w know|strong="G1097"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*.
\v 11 \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w came|strong="G2064"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w His|strong="G1519"\w* \w own|strong="G2398"\w* \w things|strong="G3588"\w*, \w yet|strong="G2532"\w* \w His|strong="G1519"\w* \w own|strong="G2398"\w* \w people|strong="G3880"\w* \w did|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w receive|strong="G3880"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*.
\v 12 \w But|strong="G1161"\w*, \w as|strong="G3745"\w* \w many|strong="G3745"\w* \w as|strong="G3745"\w* \w did|strong="G1096"\w* \w receive|strong="G2983"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*,\f + \fr 1:12 \ft ‘Receive’, not ‘accept’—if you ‘accept’ something it is inferior, or is offered by someone who is socially inferior; superior people or things are ‘received’. If you merely ‘accept Jesus’ that Jesus can't save you; he is less than you are.\f* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \nd \w them|strong="G3588"\w*\nd* \w He|strong="G1161"\w* \w gave|strong="G1325"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w right|strong="G1849"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w become|strong="G1096"\w* \w children|strong="G5043"\w* \w of|strong="G2316"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*,\f + \fr 1:12 \ft No one is born a child of God (God has no grandchildren); you may \nd become\nd* one by receiving Christ. Presumably ‘receiving’ is a conscious act. Each of my two children did this when four years old.\f* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w His|strong="G1519"\w* \w name|strong="G3686"\w*:\f + \fr 1:12 \ft Never does the Text read ‘believe \nd in\nd*’ (Greek εν) Jesus or His name; always it reads ‘believe \nd into\nd*’ (Greek εις). People believe in Santa Claus, the Easter bunny, the goodness of man, or whatever, but it makes no difference in their lives. Many millions of people say they ‘believe in Jesus’, but it makes no difference in their lives either. You have to believe \nd into\nd* Him—commitment and identification are involved, that go along with the change in location, from being outside to being inside. As Jesus Himself said in John 6:53-56, you have to “eat” His flesh and “drink” His blood. If you eat something your body assimilates it, it becomes part of you.\f*
\v 13 \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w were|strong="G3739"\w* \w begotten|strong="G1080"\w*, \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w by|strong="G1537"\w* blood, \w nor|strong="G3761"\w* \w by|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G1537"\w* \w desire|strong="G2307"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G1537"\w* \w flesh|strong="G4561"\w*, \w nor|strong="G3761"\w* \w by|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G1537"\w* \w will|strong="G2307"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w a|strong="G3756"\w* \w man|strong="G3739"\w*,\f + \fr 1:13 \ft “The will of a man” seems obvious enough—many, perhaps most, people are born because a man decides he wants children. “The desire of the flesh”—many others are born because a man and a woman are carried away by physical attraction, whether or not they are planning to have a child. “By blood”—the best sense I can make out of this is to assume that it refers to levirate marriage; a man fertilizes his brother's childless widow to produce an heir for that brother, precisely because of the \nd blood\nd* relationship between them.\f* \w but|strong="G2316"\w* \w by|strong="G1537"\w* \nd \w God|strong="G2316"\w*\nd*.\f + \fr 1:13 \ft For a human being to be begotten physically a man must implant the seed of life, and to be begotten spiritually God must implant the seed of the Life.\f*
\s1 Jesus—the Only-begotten
\p 
\v 14 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Word|strong="G3056"\w* \w became|strong="G1096"\w* \w flesh|strong="G4561"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w lived|strong="G2532"\w* \w among|strong="G1722"\w* \w us|strong="G2249"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w we|strong="G2249"\w* observed \w His|strong="G1722"\w* \w glory|strong="G1391"\w*, \w glory|strong="G1391"\w* \w of|strong="G3056"\w* \w an|strong="G2532"\w* Only-begotten,\f + \fr 1:14 \ft Jesus was very literally God's ‘only-begotten’ Son. Since the Holy Spirit fertilized the virgin Mary, Jesus was literally begotten by God, but He is the only one in all human history who was begotten in that way.\f* \w from|strong="G3844"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w*, \w full|strong="G4134"\w* \w of|strong="G3056"\w* \w grace|strong="G5485"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* truth.
\v 15 \w John|strong="G2491"\w* \w testified|strong="G3140"\w* \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w called|strong="G3004"\w* \w out|strong="G2896"\w* \w saying|strong="G3004"\w*: “\nd \w This|strong="G3778"\w*\nd* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w of|strong="G4012"\w* \w whom|strong="G3739"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w*, ‘\w The|strong="G2532"\w* \w One|strong="G3739"\w* \w coming|strong="G2064"\w* \w after|strong="G3694"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w now|strong="G2532"\w* \w ahead|strong="G1715"\w* \w of|strong="G4012"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*, \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w existed|strong="G1510"\w* \w before|strong="G1715"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w did|strong="G2532"\w*.’ ”
\v 16 \w Now|strong="G2532"\w* \w we|strong="G2249"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w received|strong="G2983"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w His|strong="G3956"\w* \w fullness|strong="G4138"\w*, yes, \w grace|strong="G5485"\w* \w upon|strong="G3588"\w* \w grace|strong="G5485"\w*.
\v 17 \w Because|strong="G3754"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Law|strong="G3551"\w* \w was|strong="G1096"\w* \w given|strong="G1325"\w* \w through|strong="G1223"\w* \w Moses|strong="G3475"\w*;\f + \fr 1:17 \ft Why “because”? What does the Law have to do with verse 16? We are not accustomed to associate the Law with grace, but as a revelation from God to men would it not be a manifestation of His grace? Of course the Son of God incarnate was a much greater manifestation of that grace—“grace upon grace”.\f* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Grace|strong="G5485"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* Truth \w came|strong="G1096"\w* \w through|strong="G1223"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w*.\f + \fr 1:17 \ft “The life”, “the light”, “the grace”, “the truth”—these things the Lord Jesus Christ offers us. In contrast Satan offers death, darkness, hate and the lie. Hey, I don't know about you, but I'm with Jesus!\f*
\v 18 \w No|strong="G3762"\w* \w one|strong="G3762"\w* \w has|strong="G2316"\w* \w ever|strong="G1519"\w* \w seen|strong="G3708"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*. \w The|strong="G1519"\w* Only-begotten \w Son|strong="G5207"\w*,\f + \fr 1:18 \ft Instead of “the only begotten son” (as in over 99.5% of the Greek manuscripts), some five manuscripts (of inferior quality, objectively so) have “an only begotten god”, while another two (also inferior) have “the only begotten god”. Since the absence of the definite article (in Greek) can have the effect of emphasizing the inherent quality of the noun, the second reading could be rendered “only begotten \nd god\nd*”—this alternative has appealed to many evangelicals who see in it a strong affirmation of the deity of Christ. But if the God-part of the Christ was begotten in the womb of the virgin Mary, then He is not eternally preexistent; and in that event Christ could not be God the Son, one of the three persons of the Trinity. Notice the precision in Isaiah 9:6—“unto us a child is born; unto us a son is given.” Jehovah the Son was given, not born. Notice further that the context is about the Incarnation, not the Son's eternal preexistence. But in any case, why follow seven manuscripts of demonstrably inferior quality against 1,700 better ones? The original and therefore true reading is certainly “the only begotten Son”.\f* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* exists \w in|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w bosom|strong="G2859"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w*, \nd \w He|strong="G3588"\w*\nd* \w has|strong="G2316"\w* interpreted \it Him\it*.\f + \fr 1:18 \ft Instead of “interpret” one could render ‘explain’, ‘describe’, ‘give a report about’… I connect this statement to verse 1—the \nd Word\nd* shows us who the Father really is. As Jesus said to Philip, “He who has seen me has seen the Father” (John 14:9).\f*
\ms1 John the Baptizer performs his office
\p 
\v 19 \w Now|strong="G2532"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w John|strong="G2491"\w*'s \w testimony|strong="G3141"\w*, \w when|strong="G3753"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jews|strong="G2453"\w*\f + \fr 1:19 \ft John uses “the Jews” to refer to the religious leaders, the hierarchy.\f* \w sent|strong="G2532"\w* \w priests|strong="G2409"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w Levites|strong="G3019"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w Jerusalem|strong="G2414"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w ask|strong="G2065"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Who|strong="G5101"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w*?”
\v 20 \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w confessed|strong="G3670"\w*, \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w did|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w deny|strong="G3588"\w* \w but|strong="G2532"\w* \w confessed|strong="G3670"\w*, “\w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w*.”\f + \fr 1:20 \ft “Christ” in Greek is a translation of the Hebrew “Messiah”. The people were looking for the Messiah.\f*
\v 21 \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w asked|strong="G2065"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w What|strong="G5101"\w* \w then|strong="G3767"\w*, \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w Elijah|strong="G2243"\w*?” \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w*, “\w I|strong="G2532"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w*.”\f + \fr 1:21 \ft Note that John declares that he is not Elijah. The point of their question relates to Malachi 4:5, where Elijah is the forerunner of the Messiah. But the context in Malachi is the second coming, not the first. John performed the function at the first coming that Elijah, literally, will perform at the second. John came “in the spirit and power of Elijah” (Luke 1:17—the angel Gabriel cites Malachi), but was not Elijah.\f* “\w Are|strong="G1510"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* ‘\w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Prophet|strong="G4396"\w*’?”\f + \fr 1:21 \ft “The Prophet” is presumably a reference to Deuteronomy 18:15—the Jews figured that this prophecy refers to the Messiah, and so do we.\f* “\w No|strong="G3756"\w*,” \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w*.
\v 22 \w So|strong="G2443"\w* \w they|strong="G3588"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w Who|strong="G5101"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w you|strong="G1325"\w*?—\w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w we|strong="G2249"\w* \w may|strong="G2443"\w* \w give|strong="G1325"\w* \w an|strong="G1325"\w* answer \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G5101"\w* \w sent|strong="G3992"\w* \w us|strong="G1325"\w*. \w What|strong="G5101"\w* \w do|strong="G5101"\w* \w you|strong="G1325"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w yourself|strong="G4572"\w*?”
\v 23 \w He|strong="G3588"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w*, “\w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1473"\w* ‘\w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w voice|strong="G5456"\w* \w of|strong="G2962"\w* \w one|strong="G3588"\w* \w calling|strong="G3004"\w* \w out|strong="G5456"\w*: “\w Make|strong="G2116"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \sc \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w*\sc*'\w s|strong="G2962"\w* \w road|strong="G3598"\w* \w straight|strong="G2116"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w wilderness|strong="G2048"\w*,” ’ \w just|strong="G2531"\w* \w as|strong="G2531"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w prophet|strong="G4396"\w* \w Isaiah|strong="G2268"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w*.”\f + \fr 1:23 \ft The reference is to Isaiah 40:3. Hebrew poetry, and prose, makes heavy use of parallel or synonymous statements. From the context in Isaiah it seems clear that “in the wilderness” goes with the verb “make straight”, not “call out”. But why a straight road in the wilderness? Any road facilitates the movement of people and goods, but a straight road through accidented terrain is a major asset. (Actually, Isaiah 40:3-4 describes the construction of a modern superhighway.) John was the voice, but it was the people who had to make the road. So how about us? Are we supposed to be making such a road, and if so, how? At the very least we should be proclaiming biblical values to the world by every available means.\f*
\p 
\v 24 \w Now|strong="G2532"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w had|strong="G2532"\w* \w been|strong="G1510"\w* \w sent|strong="G2532"\w* \w were|strong="G1510"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Pharisees|strong="G5330"\w*.
\v 25 \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w asked|strong="G2065"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w saying|strong="G3004"\w*, “\w Why|strong="G5101"\w* \w then|strong="G3767"\w* \w do|strong="G5101"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* baptize \w if|strong="G1487"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w*, \w nor|strong="G3761"\w* \w Elijah|strong="G2243"\w*, \w nor|strong="G3761"\w* ‘\w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Prophet|strong="G4396"\w*’?”
\v 26 \w John|strong="G2491"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w* \w saying|strong="G3004"\w*: “\w I|strong="G1473"\w* baptize \w with|strong="G1722"\w* \w water|strong="G5204"\w*, \w but|strong="G3588"\w* \w among|strong="G1722"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w stands|strong="G2476"\w* \w One|strong="G3739"\w* \w whom|strong="G3739"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w do|strong="G1492"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w*.
\v 27 \w He|strong="G3739"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w One|strong="G3739"\w* \w coming|strong="G2064"\w* \w after|strong="G3694"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w now|strong="G1510"\w* ahead \w of|strong="G3588"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*, \w whose|strong="G3739"\w* \w sandal|strong="G5266"\w* strap \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* worthy \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w loose|strong="G3089"\w*.”
\v 28 \w These|strong="G3778"\w* \w things|strong="G3778"\w* \w happened|strong="G1096"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* Bithabara,\f + \fr 1:28 \ft Some 65% of the Greek manuscripts read “Bethany” instead of the familiar “Bethabara” (I follow the best line of transmission in reading ‘Bithabara’, with 25% of the Greek manuscripts, while ‘Bethabara’ has 10%), but in either case we do not know the precise location. \nd However\nd*, many Bible maps place ‘Bethabara’ near Jericho, on the west side of the river, but the Text states plainly that it was “across the Jordan” (=on the east side). A combination of such maps plus the true reading sets up an apparent contradiction or error in the text, which is actually in the map.\f* \w across|strong="G4008"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Jordan|strong="G2446"\w*, \w where|strong="G3699"\w* \w John|strong="G2491"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* baptizing.
\s1 “Behold the Lamb of God!”
\p 
\v 29 \w The|strong="G2532"\w* \w next|strong="G1887"\w* \w day|strong="G1887"\w* \w John|strong="G3004"\w* \w sees|strong="G3708"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w coming|strong="G2064"\w* \w toward|strong="G4314"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w*: “\w Look|strong="G3708"\w*! \w The|strong="G2532"\w* \w Lamb|strong="G3004"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* takes away \w the|strong="G2532"\w* sin \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w world|strong="G2889"\w*!\f + \fr 1:29 \ft A tremendous statement! The Sacrifice to end all blood sacrifices is now physically present in the world.\f*
\v 30 \w This|strong="G3778"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w He|strong="G3739"\w* \w of|strong="G5228"\w* \w whom|strong="G3739"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w*, ‘\w After|strong="G3694"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w comes|strong="G2064"\w* \w a|strong="G1096"\w* \w man|strong="G3778"\w* \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w now|strong="G1096"\w* \w ahead|strong="G1715"\w* \w of|strong="G5228"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*, \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w He|strong="G3739"\w* \w existed|strong="G1510"\w* \w before|strong="G1715"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w did|strong="G1096"\w*.’\f + \fr 1:30 \ft John was six months older than Jesus, so he is affirming that Jesus had a prior existence. Since a mere man cannot have a prior existence, John is affirming Jesus' divinity.\f*
\v 31 \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w did|strong="G1492"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*; \w but|strong="G3588"\w* \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w He|strong="G3778"\w* \w should|strong="G1492"\w* \w be|strong="G3756"\w* \w revealed|strong="G5319"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w Israel|strong="G2474"\w*, \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w why|strong="G1223"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w came|strong="G2064"\w* baptizing \w with|strong="G1722"\w* \w water|strong="G5204"\w*.”
\p 
\v 32 \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w John|strong="G2491"\w* \w testified|strong="G3140"\w* \w saying|strong="G3004"\w*: “\w I|strong="G2532"\w* observed \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Spirit|strong="G4151"\w* \w coming|strong="G2597"\w* \w down|strong="G2597"\w* \w like|strong="G5613"\w* \w a|strong="G5613"\w* \w dove|strong="G4058"\w* \w out|strong="G1537"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w heaven|strong="G3772"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* rested \w upon|strong="G1909"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*.\f + \fr 1:32 \ft John does not record the baptism of Jesus, as such, but we know from the other Gospels that this incident took place at that baptism. Nor does John record Jesus' confrontation with Satan in the wilderness. In general, John does not repeat information available in the other Gospels. (John wrote after the other Gospels had been in circulation for well over a decade.)\f*
\v 33 \w Now|strong="G2532"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w did|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*,\f + \fr 1:33 \ft This is curious. John and Jesus were related, and their mothers were close, so it seems improbable that they would never have met as boys or youths. Perhaps John means as the Messiah—until His baptism Jesus gave no overt demonstration that He was the Messiah. (However, given the circumstances surrounding both Mary and Elizabeth, I suppose it is possible that the two boys never met.)\f* \w but|strong="G2532"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w sent|strong="G3992"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* baptize \w with|strong="G1722"\w* \w water|strong="G5204"\w*, \nd \w He|strong="G2532"\w*\nd* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*,\f + \fr 1:33 \ft Notice that the Baptizer affirms that God spoke to him directly, in audible or distinguishable words, which he quotes. God spoke like that 2000 years ago, and He continues to do so.\f* ‘\w The|strong="G1722"\w* \w One|strong="G3739"\w* \w upon|strong="G1909"\w* \w whom|strong="G3739"\w* \w you|strong="G3739"\w* \w see|strong="G3708"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Spirit|strong="G4151"\w* \w coming|strong="G2597"\w* \w down|strong="G2597"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* resting—\w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w who|strong="G3739"\w* baptizes \w with|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Holy|strong="G4151"\w* \w Spirit|strong="G4151"\w*.’\f + \fr 1:33 \ft In John's baptism, John is the agent; in Christ's baptism, Jesus is the agent; the baptism where the Holy Spirit is the agent is distinct from these. In John's baptism the substance used for the ritual was water; in Christ's baptism the substance used is the Holy Spirit. In John's baptism the person got wet but then dried off, so presumably the real point of the exercise was a spiritual transaction; how much more, then, in Christ's baptism. I am inclined to link Christ's baptism (He is the agent) with John 4:13-14 and 7:38-39. “Jesus answered and said to her, ‘Everyone who drinks of this water will thirst again, but whoever drinks of the water that \bd \nd I\nd*\bd* will give him will never ever thirst; rather, the water that I will give him will become in him a spring of water welling up into eternal life’ ” (4:13-14). “Jesus stood up and called out saying, ‘If anyone thirsts, let him come to me and drink. The one believing into me, just as the Scripture has said, out from his innermost being will flow rivers of living water.’ (Now He said this about the Spirit, whom those believing into Him were going to receive, in that the Holy Spirit had not yet been given because Jesus had not yet been glorified.)” (7:37-39). In other words, when Jesus baptizes you, you are regenerated, you receive a new nature, you receive the Holy Spirit.\f*
\v 34 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w I|strong="G2532"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w seen|strong="G3708"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w testified|strong="G3140"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*.”\f + \fr 1:34 \ft That is what he said, “\nd the\nd* Son of God” (actually, ‘the Son of the God’), which here probably means that there is only one. John clearly identifies and presents the Messiah to the populace. He performed his office.\f*
\ms1 Jesus begins His public ministry
\p 
\v 35 \w Again|strong="G3825"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w next|strong="G1887"\w* \w day|strong="G1887"\w* \w John|strong="G2491"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* \w standing|strong="G2476"\w* \w with|strong="G1537"\w* \w two|strong="G1417"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w his|strong="G2532"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w*.
\v 36 \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w seeing|strong="G3708"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w walking|strong="G4043"\w* \w by|strong="G2532"\w*, \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w*, “\w Look|strong="G3708"\w*, \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Lamb|strong="G3004"\w* \w of|strong="G2316"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*!”
\v 37 \w The|strong="G2532"\w* \w two|strong="G1417"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w* heard \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w speak|strong="G2980"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* followed \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w*.
\v 38 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w turning|strong="G4762"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* observing \w them|strong="G3588"\w* following\f + \fr 1:38 \ft Presumably Jesus waited for them to catch up, so He was observing them during that time. His purpose in passing by there was precisely to attract those two men (so I imagine), and He was doubtless aware when they started out after Him.\f* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w What|strong="G5101"\w* \w do|strong="G5101"\w* \w you|strong="G3004"\w* \w want|strong="G2212"\w*?” \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Rabbi|strong="G4461"\w*” (\w which|strong="G3588"\w* \w translated|strong="G3177"\w* \w means|strong="G3004"\w* ‘\w Teacher|strong="G1320"\w*’), “\w where|strong="G4226"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w You|strong="G3004"\w* \w staying|strong="G3306"\w*?”
\v 39 \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Come|strong="G2064"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w see|strong="G3708"\w*.” \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w went|strong="G2064"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w saw|strong="G3708"\w* \w where|strong="G4226"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w staying|strong="G3306"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w stayed|strong="G3306"\w* \w with|strong="G3844"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w that|strong="G3739"\w* \w day|strong="G2250"\w*—\w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w about|strong="G5613"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w tenth|strong="G1182"\w* \w hour|strong="G5610"\w*.\f + \fr 1:39 \ft This is significant. John uses Roman time, so this is 10 a.m. Which means that Jesus spent most of the day with just those two men. You had better believe they were talking the whole time. Jesus knew they would be two of His disciples and was already investing in them—to such good effect that the next day they bring in two more. The Text does not clarify whether or not they spent the night as well.\f*
\v 40 \w One|strong="G1520"\w* \w of|strong="G2250"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w two|strong="G1417"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* heard \w John|strong="G2491"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* followed \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* Andrew, \w Simon|strong="G4613"\w* \w Peter|strong="G4074"\w*'s brother.
\v 41 \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w first|strong="G4413"\w* \w finds|strong="G2147"\w* \w his|strong="G2398"\w* \w own|strong="G2398"\w* brother \w Simon|strong="G4613"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w We|strong="G2532"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w found|strong="G2147"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Messiah|strong="G5547"\w*” (\w which|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w translated|strong="G3177"\w* ‘\w Christ|strong="G5547"\w*’).
\v 42 \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w led|strong="G2424"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w*. \w Looking|strong="G1689"\w* \w at|strong="G4314"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w*, “\w You|strong="G4771"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w Simon|strong="G4613"\w*, \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w son|strong="G5207"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* Jonah;\f + \fr 1:42 \ft The Text says, “\nd the\nd* son of Jonah”. Since Peter obviously had at least one brother, he was not an only son. Perhaps we should understand that Peter was the firstborn. Perhaps 0.5% of the Greek manuscripts (of objectively inferior quality) read “John” for “Jonah” (as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.).\f* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* \w called|strong="G2564"\w* \w Cephas|strong="G2786"\w*” (\w which|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w translated|strong="G3177"\w* ‘\w Stone|strong="G4074"\w*’).\f + \fr 1:42 \ft \it Cephas\it* is Aramaic for ‘stone’; πετρος is Greek for ‘stone’ (a small object, as opposed to a ‘rock’). The name ‘Peter’ is a transliteration into English of πετρος, but since ‘peter’ does not mean ‘stone’ in English, to put ‘Peter’ in verse 42 misses the point.\f*
\s1 Nathanael
\p 
\v 43 \w The|strong="G2532"\w* \w next|strong="G1887"\w* \w day|strong="G1887"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* decided \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w go|strong="G1831"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w Galilee|strong="G1056"\w*, \w so|strong="G2532"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w finds|strong="G2147"\w* \w Philip|strong="G5376"\w*\f + \fr 1:43 \ft I cannot prove it, but I suspect that Philip was the second man, of John's disciples, who spent the day with Jesus. If so, it seems unlikely that he and Andrew spent the night with Jesus, because in that event Jesus would not have to “find” him.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, “Follow \w me|strong="G1473"\w*.”
\v 44 (\w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w Philip|strong="G5376"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w from|strong="G2532"\w* Bethsaida, \w the|strong="G2532"\w* hometown \w of|strong="G2532"\w* Andrew \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w Peter|strong="G4074"\w*.)
\v 45 \w Philip|strong="G5376"\w* \w finds|strong="G2147"\w* \w Nathanael|strong="G3482"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w We|strong="G2532"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w found|strong="G2147"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w One|strong="G3588"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w whom|strong="G3588"\w* \w Moses|strong="G3475"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Law|strong="G3551"\w*—\w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w prophets|strong="G4396"\w*—\w wrote|strong="G1125"\w*: \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w son|strong="G5207"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w Joseph|strong="G2501"\w*, \w from|strong="G1537"\w* Natsareth.”\f + \fr 1:45 \ft The Hebrew spelling of the town's name comes over into English as ‘Natsareth’, not ‘Nazareth’. This is crucial to a correct understanding of Matthew 2:23 (please see the note there).\f*
\v 46 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w Nathanael|strong="G3482"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Can|strong="G1410"\w* \w anything|strong="G3708"\w* \w good|strong="G3588"\w* \w come|strong="G2064"\w* \w out|strong="G2532"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \nd Natsareth\nd*?” \w Philip|strong="G5376"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Come|strong="G2064"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w see|strong="G3708"\w*!”\f + \fr 1:46 \ft “Come and see.” “Taste and see that the Lord is good.” In the final analysis you have to decide for yourself. Check it out.\f*
\p 
\v 47 \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w saw|strong="G3708"\w* \w Nathanael|strong="G3482"\w* \w coming|strong="G2064"\w* \w toward|strong="G4314"\w* \w Him|strong="G3708"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w him|strong="G3708"\w*, “\nd \w There|strong="G2532"\w*\nd*, \w a|strong="G2532"\w* genuine \w Israelite|strong="G2475"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w whom|strong="G5101"\w* \w there|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w no|strong="G2532"\w* \w deceit|strong="G1388"\w*!”
\v 48 \w Nathanael|strong="G3482"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w From|strong="G2064"\w* \w where|strong="G4159"\w* \w do|strong="G2532"\w* \w You|strong="G4771"\w* \w know|strong="G1097"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*?” \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Before|strong="G4253"\w* \w Philip|strong="G5376"\w* \w called|strong="G3004"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w*, \w while|strong="G1722"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w were|strong="G1510"\w* \w under|strong="G5259"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w fig|strong="G4808"\w* \w tree|strong="G4808"\w*, \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w saw|strong="G3708"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w*.”
\v 49 \w In|strong="G2532"\w* answer \w Nathanael|strong="G3482"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w Rabbi|strong="G4461"\w*, \w You|strong="G4771"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*! \w You|strong="G4771"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w King|strong="G3588"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w Israel|strong="G2474"\w*!”\f + \fr 1:49 \ft Wow, that was a real switch—from disdainful doubt in verse 46 to faith and submission in verse 49. What caused the change? A mature fig tree's branches reach to the ground and form a curtain—there is a clear space around the trunk that is cool and private [I have been there]. It was a great place to be alone with God. But for Jesus to see Nathanael there (there were probably hills in between as well) meant that He was supernatural. That statement convinced Nathanael that he was looking at the Messiah, and he immediately declared allegiance. Of the four Gospels, only John uses the name ‘Nathanael’, the others do not; they all use the name ‘Bartholomew’, while John never does. Since Nathanael was one of the apostles, evidently (John 21:2), we may conclude that we have two names for the same person.\f*
\v 50 \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w You|strong="G4771"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w* \w because|strong="G2532"\w* \w I|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w I|strong="G2532"\w* \w saw|strong="G3708"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w under|strong="G5270"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w fig|strong="G4808"\w* \w tree|strong="G4808"\w*? \w You|strong="G4771"\w* \w will|strong="G2316"\w* \w see|strong="G3708"\w* \w greater|strong="G3173"\w* \w than|strong="G3173"\w* \w these|strong="G3588"\w*.”\f + \fr 1:50 \ft The demonstrative pronoun is plural but ambiguous as to gender. Since I would expect the singular (presumably it was the single statement that caused Nathanael's belief) the plural leaves me in doubt. Is it greater things or people, or both?\f*
\v 51 \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w I|strong="G2532"\w* \w tell|strong="G3004"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* (pl) \w most|strong="G2316"\w* assuredly, later \w on|strong="G1909"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w will|strong="G2316"\w* \w see|strong="G3708"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w heaven|strong="G3772"\w* opened \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* angels \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* ascending \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w descending|strong="G2597"\w* \w upon|strong="G1909"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Man|strong="G3778"\w*.”\f + \fr 1:51 \ft So far as I know, we have no record of when this took place, but no doubt it did. Jesus addressed Nathanael in particular, “He says to \nd him\nd*”, but used the plural, “ye”, about seeing the heaven opened. “The Son of the Man” appears to be a phrase coined by the Lord Jesus to refer to Himself; the Text does say “the son of the man”, which does not make very good sense in English, at first glance, but if “\nd the\nd* man” refers to pristine Adam and “\nd the\nd* son” to an only pristine descendant, it makes great sense. It seems to indicate a perfect human prototype, like Adam was before the fall—the human side of the God-man.\f*
\c 2
\s1 Water into wine
\m 
\v 1 \w On|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w third|strong="G5154"\w* \w day|strong="G2250"\w*\f + \fr 2:1 \ft Counting from when? 1:19-28 happened on one day; 1:29-34 happened the next (2\sup nd\sup*) day; 1:35-42 happened the next (3\sup rd\sup*) day; 1:43-51 happened the next (4\sup th\sup*) day. So the third day here must count from the last day mentioned (1:43-51), although it could (and in Jewish thought probably did) include it. The wedding started that day, but such weddings often lasted several days (and the wine would run out toward the end, if it did). Jesus and His disciples (four?) probably had about an 80-mile walk, 55 miles up the Jordan valley (relatively smooth and straight) and 25 of rougher terrain. Since they did all their traveling on foot, and were therefore used to it, they could easily make the distance in two days.\f* \w a|strong="G1096"\w* \w wedding|strong="G1062"\w* \w took|strong="G1096"\w* \w place|strong="G1096"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w Cana|strong="G2580"\w* \w of|strong="G2250"\w* \w Galilee|strong="G1056"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w*' \w mother|strong="G3384"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w there|strong="G1563"\w*.
\v 2 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w both|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w His|strong="G1519"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w* \w had|strong="G2424"\w* \w been|strong="G2532"\w* \w invited|strong="G2564"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w wedding|strong="G1062"\w*.\f + \fr 2:2 \ft The disciples had been invited in their own right, before they were disciples.\f*
\v 3 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w when|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w wine|strong="G3631"\w* \w had|strong="G2192"\w* given \w out|strong="G2532"\w*, \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w*' \w mother|strong="G3384"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w They|strong="G2532"\w* don'\w t|strong="G3588"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w any|strong="G2192"\w* \w wine|strong="G3631"\w*!”
\v 4 \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w her|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w What|strong="G5101"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*, \w woman|strong="G1135"\w*?\f + \fr 2:4 \ft Jesus was not being disrespectful; this was a normal form of address.\f* \w My|strong="G1473"\w* \w time|strong="G5610"\w* \w has|strong="G5101"\w* \w not|strong="G3768"\w* \w yet|strong="G2532"\w* \w come|strong="G2240"\w*.”\f + \fr 2:4 \ft I conclude from 1:43 that Jesus was at that wedding on purpose, and probably had an idea of what would happen. Perhaps He was testing His mother's faith, and maybe her determination. However, as He declares, He was not yet ready to really go public—He would do that in Jerusalem, as recorded in 2:13-25. He would start with a bang, right in the Temple!\f*
\v 5 \w His|strong="G4160"\w* \w mother|strong="G3384"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w servants|strong="G1249"\w*, “\w Do|strong="G4160"\w* \w whatever|strong="G3739"\w* \w He|strong="G3739"\w* \w may|strong="G5100"\w* \w tell|strong="G3004"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*.”\f + \fr 2:5 \ft Mary was evidently in a position to issue orders, which leads me to suspect that she was the mother of the bride, which would also explain why Jesus made a special effort to get there. From verse 12 below, it appears that the whole family was there.\f*
\p 
\v 6 (\w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w there|strong="G1563"\w* \w were|strong="G1510"\w* \w six|strong="G1803"\w* \w stone|strong="G3035"\w* \w waterpots|strong="G5201"\w* \w set|strong="G2749"\w* \w there|strong="G1563"\w*, \w according|strong="G2596"\w* \w to|strong="G2596"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w purification|strong="G2512"\w* rites \w of|strong="G2596"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w Jews|strong="G2453"\w*, \w containing|strong="G5562"\w* 20 \w or|strong="G2228"\w* 30 \w gallons|strong="G3355"\w* \w each|strong="G2596"\w*.)
\v 7 \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Fill|strong="G1072"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* pots \w with|strong="G2532"\w* \w water|strong="G5204"\w*.” \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w filled|strong="G1072"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* brim.\f + \fr 2:7 \ft That was a lot of water! If it was toward the end of the festivity, there would presumably be a great deal of wine left over. Such excellent wine would bring a good price; perhaps Jesus chose this way to give the new couple a financial boost.\f*
\v 8 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Now|strong="G1161"\w*, draw \w some|strong="G3588"\w* \w out|strong="G2532"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w take|strong="G5342"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* master \w of|strong="G2532"\w* ceremonies.” \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w took|strong="G2532"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w*.
\v 9 \w Well|strong="G2532"\w*, \w when|strong="G1161"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* master \w of|strong="G2532"\w* ceremonies \w tasted|strong="G1089"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w water|strong="G5204"\w*\f + \fr 2:9 \ft Wine has color and smell, as well as flavor—I wonder at what point the water took on those characteristics. Perhaps it was only as the servant handed the goblet to the master, so that the servants had drawn and carried ‘water’; they obeyed what seemed to them to be a strange order.\f* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w had|strong="G2532"\w* \w become|strong="G1096"\w* \w wine|strong="G3631"\w*—\w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w did|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w where|strong="G4159"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w came|strong="G1096"\w* \w from|strong="G2532"\w*, \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w servants|strong="G1249"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w had|strong="G2532"\w* drawn \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w water|strong="G5204"\w* \w knew|strong="G1492"\w*—\w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w calls|strong="G5455"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w bridegroom|strong="G3566"\w*
\v 10 \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*: “Everybody \w serves|strong="G5087"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w good|strong="G2570"\w* \w wine|strong="G3631"\w* \w first|strong="G4413"\w*, \w then|strong="G2532"\w*, \w when|strong="G3752"\w* \w people|strong="G3956"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* intoxicated, \w the|strong="G2532"\w* inferior. \nd \w You|strong="G4771"\w*\nd* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w kept|strong="G5083"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w good|strong="G2570"\w* \w wine|strong="G3631"\w* \w until|strong="G2193"\w* \w now|strong="G2532"\w*!”
\p 
\v 11 \w This|strong="G3778"\w*, \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w first|strong="G3588"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* miraculous \w signs|strong="G4592"\w*, \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w performed|strong="G4160"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w Cana|strong="G2580"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w Galilee|strong="G1056"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w revealed|strong="G5319"\w* \w His|strong="G1519"\w* \w glory|strong="G1391"\w*;\f + \fr 2:11 \ft Jesus “revealed His glory”. In what sense? As Jehovah the Son He was the Creator of this world. Transforming water into wine was an act of creation. The chemical components that distinguish wine from water had to be created on the spot, and mixed with the water. This “first miraculous sign” was simply tremendous—it revealed Jesus as Creator. However, although presumably all the guests drank of this new wine, being tipsy they may not have realized what went on. Only the disciples, the servants, and of course Mary, knew what had really happened. Apparently this miracle was not broadcast at that time—like Jesus said, not yet. (Neither Matthew, Mark nor Luke were there, but John, the author of this Gospel, probably was; in which case we have an eyewitness account [John and James were partners with Peter and Andrew; so since Peter and Andrew were invited they probably were too].)\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w His|strong="G1519"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w* \w believed|strong="G4100"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*.
\p 
\v 12 \w After|strong="G3326"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w went|strong="G2597"\w* \w down|strong="G2597"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w Capernaum|strong="G2584"\w*—\w He|strong="G2532"\w*, \w His|strong="G1519"\w* \w mother|strong="G3384"\w*, \w His|strong="G1519"\w* brothers, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w His|strong="G1519"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w*—\w but|strong="G2532"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w did|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w stay|strong="G3306"\w* \w there|strong="G1563"\w* \w many|strong="G4183"\w* \w days|strong="G2250"\w*.\f + \fr 2:12 \ft The next verse tells us that the Passover was near. The Passover was one (probably the most important) of the three festivals during the year when every God-fearing male had to present himself at the temple in Jerusalem (Deuteronomy 16:16). Often the whole family would go, so perhaps the whole group mentioned in verse 12 went on to Jerusalem. Jesus had just come up from Judea, only to turn around and go back, which gives us some indication of the importance of the wedding in Cana. That Joseph is not mentioned at all leads one to suspect that he had died by now.\f*
\s1 The first cleansing of the Temple—Passover, 27 AD
\p 
\v 13 \w Now|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jewish|strong="G2453"\w* \w Passover|strong="G3957"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w near|strong="G1451"\w*, \w so|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w went|strong="G2424"\w* \w up|strong="G1519"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w Jerusalem|strong="G2414"\w*.
\v 14 \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Temple|strong="G2413"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w found|strong="G2147"\w* \w people|strong="G3588"\w* \w selling|strong="G4453"\w* \w oxen|strong="G1016"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w sheep|strong="G4263"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w doves|strong="G4058"\w*, \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* moneychangers \w at|strong="G1722"\w* work.
\v 15 \w When|strong="G2532"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w had|strong="G2532"\w* \w made|strong="G4160"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w scourge|strong="G5416"\w* \w out|strong="G1537"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w cords|strong="G4979"\w*, \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w drove|strong="G1544"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w out|strong="G1537"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w temple|strong="G2413"\w*, \w both|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w sheep|strong="G4263"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w oxen|strong="G1016"\w*;\f + \fr 2:15 \ft The impression I get is that it was mainly the animals that He drove, not the people; in the next verse He commands the dove-sellers to remove them, presumably still in the cages.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w as|strong="G2532"\w* \w for|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w moneychangers|strong="G2855"\w*, \w He|strong="G2532"\w* overturned \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w tables|strong="G5132"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w scattered|strong="G3956"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w coins|strong="G2772"\w*.
\v 16 \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* dove-sellers \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w*: “\w Get|strong="G2532"\w* \w these|strong="G3778"\w* \w things|strong="G3778"\w* \w out|strong="G2532"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w here|strong="G1782"\w*! \w Stop|strong="G3361"\w* turning \w my|strong="G1473"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w*'s \w House|strong="G3624"\w* \w into|strong="G4160"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* marketplace!”
\v 17 \w Then|strong="G3754"\w* \w His|strong="G3754"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w* \w remembered|strong="G3403"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w it|strong="G3754"\w* stands \w written|strong="G1125"\w*, “\w Zeal|strong="G2205"\w* \w for|strong="G3754"\w* \w Your|strong="G3588"\w* \w House|strong="G3624"\w* consumes \w me|strong="G1473"\w*.”\f + \fr 2:17 \ft See Psalm 69:9.\f*
\p 
\v 18 \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jews|strong="G2453"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w What|strong="G5101"\w* \w sign|strong="G4592"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w* \w you|strong="G3754"\w* \w show|strong="G1166"\w* \w us|strong="G3004"\w*, \w since|strong="G3754"\w* \w you|strong="G3754"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w* \w these|strong="G3778"\w* \w things|strong="G3778"\w*?”\f + \fr 2:18 \ft The commerce going on in the Temple was crooked, and was under the direction of the religious leaders. What Jesus did was an affront, a direct challenge to their authority. He got their attention! From this moment on they knew about Jesus! What He did was so unexpected, so outrageous, that the Jews did not know how to react. Maybe some were just a little afraid He might be the Messiah. (And just maybe a few of them had been there 18 years before and listened to a certain twelve-year-old Boy.)\f*
\v 19 \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Destroy|strong="G3089"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w temple|strong="G3485"\w*,\f + \fr 2:19 \ft The Lord gives an unexpected meaning to “this temple”, metaphoric, but this prophecy was literally fulfilled.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w three|strong="G5140"\w* \w days|strong="G2250"\w* \w I|strong="G2532"\w* \w will|strong="G2532"\w* \w raise|strong="G1453"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w*.”\f + \fr 2:19 \ft Since Jesus was referring to His own body, once He was dead how could He do this? His spirit did not die, and at the right moment returned to the body and raised it, uniting with it once again (and in so doing He glorified it).\f*
\v 20 \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Jews|strong="G2453"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w*, “\w It|strong="G2532"\w* \w took|strong="G2532"\w* forty-six \w years|strong="G2094"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w build|strong="G3618"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w temple|strong="G3485"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \nd \w you|strong="G4771"\w*\nd* \w will|strong="G2532"\w* \w raise|strong="G1453"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w three|strong="G5140"\w* \w days|strong="G2250"\w*?!”
\v 21 \w But|strong="G1161"\w* \w He|strong="G1161"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* \w speaking|strong="G3004"\w* \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w temple|strong="G3485"\w* \w of|strong="G4012"\w* \w His|strong="G4012"\w* \w body|strong="G4983"\w*.
\v 22 \w Therefore|strong="G3767"\w*, \w when|strong="G3753"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* \w raised|strong="G1453"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w among|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w dead|strong="G3498"\w* \w His|strong="G2532"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w* \w remembered|strong="G3403"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w had|strong="G2424"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w*; \w so|strong="G3767"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w believed|strong="G4100"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Scripture|strong="G1124"\w*, \w even|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w word|strong="G3056"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w had|strong="G2424"\w* \w spoken|strong="G3004"\w*.\f + \fr 2:22 \ft Note that my rendering, “They believed the Scripture, even the word that Jesus had spoken”, has the effect of equating His word with Scripture. More precisely, the Lord's statement in verse 19 was repeated as an accusation three years later, as recorded in Matthew 26:61 and 27:40, and Matthew's Gospel had already been circulating as Scripture for decades when John wrote. If this line of reasoning is correct, then John is calling Matthew ‘Scripture’! (Of course there was an interval of a number of years (eight) between the resurrection and the publishing of Matthew's Gospel, but perhaps some did not ‘remember’ until they saw it written down.) I am not aware of any OT prophecy that could be in view here.\f*
\p 
\v 23 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w while|strong="G1722"\w* \w He|strong="G1161"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w Jerusalem|strong="G2414"\w* \w at|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Passover|strong="G3957"\w*, \w during|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w feast|strong="G1859"\w*, \w many|strong="G4183"\w* \w believed|strong="G4100"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w His|strong="G1519"\w* \w name|strong="G3686"\w*, \w observing|strong="G2334"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w signs|strong="G4592"\w* \w that|strong="G3739"\w* \w He|strong="G1161"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w doing|strong="G4160"\w*.\f + \fr 2:23 \ft I take it that it was at this point that the Lord really began to heal on a large scale. He forced the religious leaders to take notice of Him in more ways than one. Nicodemus refers to these signs.\f*
\v 24 \w But|strong="G1161"\w* \w as|strong="G1161"\w* \w for|strong="G1223"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w Himself|strong="G1438"\w*, \w He|strong="G1161"\w* \w did|strong="G1097"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w entrust|strong="G4100"\w* \w Himself|strong="G1438"\w* \w to|strong="G3756"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*,\f + \fr 2:24 \ft I would suggest that our Lord offers us an important example here: He did not entrust Himself to just anybody, even believers. He will command His followers to keep on forgiving those who sin against them, especially ‘brothers’. To forgive does not equal to trust!\f* \w because|strong="G1223"\w* \nd \w He|strong="G1161"\w*\nd* \w knew|strong="G1097"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \it men\it*
\v 25 \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w had|strong="G2192"\w* \w no|strong="G3756"\w* \w need|strong="G5532"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w anyone|strong="G5100"\w* \w should|strong="G5100"\w* \w testify|strong="G3140"\w* \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w man|strong="G5100"\w*, \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* Himself \w knew|strong="G1097"\w* \w what|strong="G5101"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w man|strong="G5100"\w*.\f + \fr 2:25 \ft As Creator He would indeed know what was in man.\f*
\c 3
\s1 Jesus and Nicodemus
\m 
\v 1 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w there|strong="G1161"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w a|strong="G1510"\w* man \w among|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G1537"\w* \w Pharisees|strong="G5330"\w* \w whose|strong="G3588"\w* \w name|strong="G3686"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w Nicodemus|strong="G3530"\w*, \w a|strong="G1510"\w* ruler \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G1537"\w* \w Jews|strong="G2453"\w*.
\v 2 \w The|strong="G2532"\w* \w same|strong="G3778"\w* \w went|strong="G2064"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G3004"\w* \w at|strong="G4314"\w* \w night|strong="G3571"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Rabbi|strong="G4461"\w*, \w we|strong="G3739"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w come|strong="G2064"\w* \w as|strong="G2532"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w teacher|strong="G1320"\w* \w from|strong="G2064"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*, \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w no|strong="G3762"\w* \w one|strong="G3762"\w* \w can|strong="G1410"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w* \w these|strong="G3778"\w* \w signs|strong="G4592"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w* \w unless|strong="G1437"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w with|strong="G3326"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*.”
\v 3 \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*,\f + \fr 3:3 \ft He does not waste time with the compliment, although it was true enough, but goes directly to a serious theological question.\f* “\w Most|strong="G2316"\w* assuredly \w I|strong="G2532"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w*, \w unless|strong="G1437"\w* \w someone|strong="G5100"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w begotten|strong="G1080"\w* \w from|strong="G2532"\w* Above,\f + \fr 3:3 \ft The basic meaning of the Greek word here, ανωθεν, is ‘from up/above’. A lot of people who say that they have been ‘born again’ have never been begotten from Above. ‘Begotten’ refers to the cause; ‘born’ refers to the result—I take it that the Lord is talking about the cause.\f* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w able|strong="G1410"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w see|strong="G3708"\w*\f + \fr 3:3 \ft Is ‘see’ just a synonym for ‘enter’ in verse 5 below, or is a difference intended?\f* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* kingdom \w of|strong="G2316"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*.”
\v 4 \w Nicodemus|strong="G3530"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w How|strong="G4459"\w* \w can|strong="G1410"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w man|strong="G3361"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* \w begotten|strong="G1080"\w*, \w being|strong="G1510"\w* \w old|strong="G1088"\w*? \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w can|strong="G1410"\w*'\w t|strong="G3588"\w* \w enter|strong="G1525"\w* \w his|strong="G1519"\w* \w mother|strong="G3384"\w*'s \w womb|strong="G2836"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w second|strong="G1208"\w* \w time|strong="G1208"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* \w born|strong="G1080"\w*, \w can|strong="G1410"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w*?”
\v 5 \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w*: “\w Most|strong="G2316"\w* assuredly \w I|strong="G2532"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w*, \w unless|strong="G1437"\w* \w someone|strong="G5100"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w begotten|strong="G1080"\w* \w by|strong="G1537"\w* \w water|strong="G5204"\w*\f + \fr 3:5 \ft Why ‘water’? Some have understood this to refer to water baptism, but it seems more likely to me that it refers to the Word (see Ephesians 5:26, John 15:3, John 17:17). As it says in Romans 10:17, “Faith comes by hearing, and hearing by the Word of God.”\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w Spirit|strong="G4151"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w able|strong="G1410"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \nd \w enter|strong="G1525"\w*\nd* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* kingdom \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*.
\v 6 \w That|strong="G3588"\w* \w which|strong="G3588"\w* \w has|strong="G4151"\w* \w been|strong="G1510"\w* \w begotten|strong="G1080"\w* \w by|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w flesh|strong="G4561"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w flesh|strong="G4561"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w which|strong="G3588"\w* \w has|strong="G4151"\w* \w been|strong="G1510"\w* \w begotten|strong="G1080"\w* \w by|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Spirit|strong="G4151"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w spirit|strong="G4151"\w*.\f + \fr 3:6 \ft In 1:13 it is “begotten by God”, here “begotten by the Spirit”, in 3:3 and 7 “begotten from Above”—I take it that the expressions are synonymous. Without God's direct participation no one is saved.\f*
\v 7 \w Do|strong="G3004"\w* \w not|strong="G3361"\w* \w be|strong="G1163"\w* perplexed \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w I|strong="G3754"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, ‘\w You|strong="G5210"\w* (pl) need \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w be|strong="G1163"\w* \w begotten|strong="G1080"\w* \w from|strong="G3361"\w* Above.’
\v 8 \w The|strong="G2532"\w* \w wind|strong="G4154"\w* \w blows|strong="G4154"\w* \w where|strong="G3699"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w wishes|strong="G2309"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G1510"\w* (sg) \w hear|strong="G5456"\w* \w its|strong="G3956"\w* \w sound|strong="G5456"\w*, \w but|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G1510"\w* \w do|strong="G1492"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w where|strong="G3699"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w comes|strong="G2064"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w or|strong="G2532"\w* \w where|strong="G3699"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w goes|strong="G5217"\w*. \w So|strong="G3779"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w with|strong="G1537"\w* \w everyone|strong="G3956"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w has|strong="G4151"\w* \w been|strong="G1510"\w* \w begotten|strong="G1080"\w* \w by|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Spirit|strong="G4151"\w*.”\f + \fr 3:8 \ft Notice that the Lord is saying here that it is \bd we\bd* who are to be unpredictable, like the wind, or the Spirit (“comes” and “goes” are in the present tense). If you are really under the control of the Spirit you will do unexpected things, just like He does. We all know of types of Christian that are rigid, totally predictable—the Lord Jesus Christ says that such ‘Christians’ have not been begotten by the Spirit. A word to the wise…\f*
\p 
\v 9 \w Nicodemus|strong="G3530"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w Him|strong="G2532"\w*, “\w How|strong="G4459"\w* \w can|strong="G1410"\w* \w these|strong="G3778"\w* \w things|strong="G3778"\w* \w be|strong="G1096"\w*?”\f + \fr 3:9 \ft His philosophical orientation was based on keeping the Law, on human responsibility. Jesus introduces the divine factor, declaring it to be indispensable.\f*
\v 10 \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w You|strong="G4771"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \nd \w the|strong="G2532"\w*\nd* \w teacher|strong="G1320"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w Israel|strong="G2474"\w*,\f + \fr 3:10 \ft The Lord used the definite article with ‘teacher’, which I understand to mean that Nicodemus was the number one teacher at that time.\f* \w yet|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w do|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w understand|strong="G1097"\w* \w these|strong="G3778"\w* \w things|strong="G3778"\w*?
\v 11 Most assuredly \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w*, \w we|strong="G2249"\w* \w speak|strong="G2980"\w* \w what|strong="G3739"\w* \w we|strong="G2249"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w testify|strong="G3140"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w what|strong="G3739"\w* \w we|strong="G2249"\w*\f + \fr 3:11 \ft Why “we”? Jesus begins the verse with “I” and begins verse 12 with “I”; so to whom does the “we” refer? Is it the ‘plural of majesty’, as some say? Perhaps He is including one or both of the other members of the Trinity—actually, it is probably the Father; see John 12:49-50. (This is early in His public ministry and He does not yet have a recognized group of disciples traveling with Him.)\f* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w seen|strong="G3708"\w*, \w but|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* (pl) \w do|strong="G1492"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w receive|strong="G2983"\w* \w our|strong="G2532"\w* \w testimony|strong="G3141"\w*.\f + \fr 3:11 \ft He had doubtless been teaching, as well as performing miracles, during those days.\f*
\v 12 \w If|strong="G1487"\w* \w I|strong="G2532"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w told|strong="G3004"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w earthly|strong="G1919"\w* \w things|strong="G3588"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w do|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w*, \w how|strong="G4459"\w* \w will|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w* \w if|strong="G1487"\w* \w I|strong="G2532"\w* \w should|strong="G3588"\w* \w tell|strong="G3004"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w heavenly|strong="G2032"\w*?
\v 13 \w No|strong="G3762"\w* \w one|strong="G3762"\w* \w has|strong="G3762"\w* gone \w up|strong="G1519"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w Heaven|strong="G3772"\w* \w except|strong="G1487"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w One|strong="G3762"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w came|strong="G2597"\w* \w down|strong="G2597"\w* \w out|strong="G1537"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w Heaven|strong="G3772"\w* —\w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Man|strong="G3762"\w*, \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w Heaven|strong="G3772"\w*.\f + \fr 3:13 \ft About 1% of the Greek manuscripts, of objectively inferior quality, omit “who is in Heaven” (as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.). Presumably those copyists could not figure out how Jesus could be on earth and in Heaven at the same time, so they altered the Text. But let us stop and think about what this verse says—Jehovah the Son came down out of Heaven all right, but when did He go up? If “the Angel of Jehovah” in the OT was Jehovah the Son, as I believe, then He had been back and forth many times. In John 5:19 Jesus said that He could only do what He saw the Father do—so when and how could Jesus see the Father? Even though Jehovah the Son was in the human body of Jesus Christ, evidently there was some sense in which He was also in Heaven; He existed there. Well, that is what John 1:18 says, “who exists in the bosom of the Father.”\f*
\v 14 \w Also|strong="G2532"\w*, \w just|strong="G2531"\w* \w as|strong="G2531"\w* \w Moses|strong="G3475"\w* \w lifted|strong="G5312"\w* \w up|strong="G1210"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w snake|strong="G3789"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w wilderness|strong="G2048"\w*,\f + \fr 3:14 \ft See Numbers 21:8-9. Once bitten, the only way to avoid an early death was to look at the bronze snake. Similarly, the only way to avoid wasting your life is to believe into Jesus.\f* \w just|strong="G2531"\w* \w so|strong="G3779"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Man|strong="G5207"\w* \w must|strong="G1163"\w* \w be|strong="G2532"\w* \w lifted|strong="G5312"\w* \w up|strong="G1210"\w*,
\v 15 \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w everyone|strong="G3956"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w believes|strong="G4100"\w* \w into|strong="G1722"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w should|strong="G3588"\w* \w not|strong="G2192"\w* \w be|strong="G3956"\w* wasted,\f + \fr 3:15 \ft Less than 2% of the Greek manuscripts, of inferior quality, omit “should not be wasted but” (as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.). The phrase is repeated in verse 16, but this is a conversation between two Jews and it is standard Hebrew procedure to repeat things. But why do I render “be wasted” instead of “perish”? Well, what do you think “perish” means? It cannot mean ‘to die’, because Christians die. It cannot mean ‘to suffer’, because Christians suffer, etc. Although the Greek verb here, απολλυμι, is used in contexts of decay, loss, ruin, destruction, death, I take it that the core idea is ‘waste’—the potential of a person or thing is wasted, does not come to fruition. The potential that your life represents, the reason why you exist, can only be realized if you believe into Jesus—otherwise you will be wasted.\f* \w but|strong="G3588"\w* \w should|strong="G3588"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* eternal \w life|strong="G2222"\w*.
\v 16 \w Because|strong="G1063"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* loved \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w world|strong="G2889"\w* \w so|strong="G3779"\w* much \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w He|strong="G3588"\w* \w gave|strong="G1325"\w* \w His|strong="G3956"\w* \w only|strong="G3439"\w* \w begotten|strong="G3439"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w*, \w so|strong="G3779"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w everyone|strong="G3956"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w believes|strong="G4100"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w should|strong="G2316"\w* \w not|strong="G3361"\w* \w be|strong="G3361"\w* wasted, \w but|strong="G3361"\w* \w should|strong="G2316"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* eternal \w life|strong="G2222"\w*.\f + \fr 3:16 \ft The opposite of ‘eternal life’ is not ‘non-eternal life’, it is ‘eternal death’. But ‘death’ does not mean ‘cease to exist’—the human spirit, the image of the Creator, is immortal, it exists forever. There are but two destinies for the human being—unending life or unending death. The central idea in ‘death’ is separation; physical death means the spirit is separated from the body; spiritual death means the spirit is separated from the Creator, forever. The essence of ‘life’ is to be in communion with the Creator, so we can start enjoying our eternal life right here, right now.\f*
\v 17 \w For|strong="G1063"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w did|strong="G2316"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* send \w His|strong="G1223"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w world|strong="G2889"\w* \w in|strong="G1519"\w* \w order|strong="G2443"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w condemn|strong="G2919"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w world|strong="G2889"\w*,\f + \fr 3:17 \ft The world was already condemned; the Son came to offer a way out.\f* \w but|strong="G1063"\w* \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w world|strong="G2889"\w* \w might|strong="G2316"\w* \w be|strong="G3756"\w* \w saved|strong="G4982"\w* \w through|strong="G1223"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*.
\v 18 \w The|strong="G1519"\w* \w one|strong="G3588"\w* \w believing|strong="G4100"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w condemned|strong="G2919"\w*, \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w one|strong="G3588"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w believing|strong="G4100"\w* \w has|strong="G2316"\w* \w already|strong="G2235"\w* \w been|strong="G2235"\w* \w condemned|strong="G2919"\w*,\f + \fr 3:18 \ft Since we are sinners by inclination and by choice, we are already under condemnation; the only way out is to believe into the Lord Jesus.\f* \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w he|strong="G1161"\w* \w has|strong="G2316"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w believed|strong="G4100"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w name|strong="G3686"\w*\f + \fr 3:18 \ft “Believe into the name” = “believe into Him”; a person's name represents that person.\f* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w only|strong="G3439"\w* \w begotten|strong="G3439"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*.
\p 
\v 19 “\w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \it basis for\it* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* condemning, \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Light|strong="G5457"\w* \w has|strong="G3778"\w* \w come|strong="G2064"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w world|strong="G2889"\w*,\f + \fr 3:19 \ft The light makes itself available, comes into our area, announces the address, but we must take the initiative to go to that light.\f* \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w people|strong="G1510"\w* loved \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w darkness|strong="G4655"\w* \w rather|strong="G3123"\w* \w than|strong="G2228"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Light|strong="G5457"\w*, \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w their|strong="G2532"\w* \w deeds|strong="G2041"\w* \w were|strong="G1510"\w* \w malignant|strong="G4190"\w*.
\v 20 \w For|strong="G1063"\w* \w whoever|strong="G3956"\w* \w practices|strong="G4238"\w* \w evil|strong="G5337"\w* \w hates|strong="G3404"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Light|strong="G5457"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w does|strong="G2064"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w come|strong="G2064"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Light|strong="G5457"\w*, \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w his|strong="G3956"\w* \w deeds|strong="G2041"\w* \w may|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w be|strong="G2532"\w* \w exposed|strong="G1651"\w*.\f + \fr 3:20 \ft In John 7:7 Jesus said, “The world cannot hate you, but does hate me, because I testify about it that its works are malignant”, and in 8:12 He said, “I am the Light of the world”. Those who love darkness generally hate Jesus.\f*
\v 21 \w But|strong="G1161"\w* \w whoever|strong="G3748"\w* \w does|strong="G4160"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* truth \w comes|strong="G2064"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Light|strong="G5457"\w* \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w his|strong="G1722"\w* \w deeds|strong="G2041"\w* \w may|strong="G2443"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* clearly seen, \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w they|strong="G1161"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w done|strong="G4160"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*.”
\s1 John the Baptizer testifies again
\p 
\v 22 \w After|strong="G3326"\w* \w these|strong="G3778"\w* \w things|strong="G3778"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w*, \w with|strong="G3326"\w* \w His|strong="G1519"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w*, \w went|strong="G2064"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Judean|strong="G2453"\w* countryside, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w there|strong="G1563"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w spent|strong="G1304"\w* \w time|strong="G1304"\w* \w with|strong="G3326"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*\f + \fr 3:22 \ft Again, He was investing in those men (not yet the full twelve).\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* baptized.
\v 23 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w John|strong="G2491"\w* \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* baptizing \w in|strong="G1722"\w* Aenon, \w near|strong="G1451"\w* Salem, \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w there|strong="G1563"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* plenty \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w water|strong="G5204"\w* \w there|strong="G1563"\w*.\f + \fr 3:23 \ft To this day there is plenty of water in the Aijalon valley, some 15-20 miles WNW of Jerusalem (Salem is an ancient name for Jerusalem; see Genesis 14:18 and Hebrews 7:1)—perhaps that is where it was. I take it that Jesus and John were in the same area, at this point.\f* \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \it people\it* \w were|strong="G1510"\w* \w coming|strong="G3854"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w being|strong="G1510"\w* baptized;
\v 24 \w for|strong="G1063"\w* \w John|strong="G2491"\w* \w had|strong="G1510"\w* \w not|strong="G1510"\w* \w yet|strong="G3768"\w* \w been|strong="G1510"\w* thrown \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w prison|strong="G5438"\w*.
\p 
\v 25 \w Then|strong="G3767"\w* \w some|strong="G3588"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w John|strong="G2491"\w*'s \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w* \w had|strong="G3588"\w* \w an|strong="G1096"\w* argument \w with|strong="G3326"\w* \w a|strong="G1096"\w* \w Judean|strong="G2453"\w* \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w purification|strong="G2512"\w*.
\v 26 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w came|strong="G2064"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w John|strong="G2491"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Rabbi|strong="G4461"\w*, \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w One|strong="G3739"\w* \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w with|strong="G3326"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w across|strong="G4008"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jordan|strong="G2446"\w*, \w about|strong="G4314"\w* \w whom|strong="G3739"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w testified|strong="G3140"\w*—\w well|strong="G2532"\w*, \w here|strong="G1510"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* baptizing, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w everyone|strong="G3956"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* flocking \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*!”\f + \fr 3:26 \ft I imagine that the ‘argument’ mentioned in verse 25 had to do with the efficacy of the two baptisms.\f*
\v 27 \w John|strong="G2491"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w*: “\w A|strong="G2532"\w* \w person|strong="G1520"\w* \w can|strong="G1410"\w* \w receive|strong="G2983"\w* \w nothing|strong="G3762"\w* \w unless|strong="G1437"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w has|strong="G3762"\w* \w been|strong="G1510"\w* \w given|strong="G1325"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w Heaven|strong="G3772"\w*.\f + \fr 3:27 \ft John states a basic truth, which is why it is not good to boast (1 Corinthians 4:7).\f*
\v 28 \w You|strong="G5210"\w* \w yourselves|strong="G4771"\w* \w can|strong="G3004"\w* \w testify|strong="G3140"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w*, ‘\bd \w I|strong="G1473"\w*\bd* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w*, \w but|strong="G3588"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w have|strong="G1473"\w* \w been|strong="G1510"\w* sent \w ahead|strong="G1715"\w* \w of|strong="G3588"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*.’
\v 29 \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w has|strong="G2192"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w bride|strong="G3565"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w bridegroom|strong="G3566"\w*, \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w friend|strong="G5384"\w* \w of|strong="G1223"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w bridegroom|strong="G3566"\w*, \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w stands|strong="G2476"\w* \w by|strong="G1223"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* hears \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, \w has|strong="G2192"\w* \w great|strong="G2532"\w* \w joy|strong="G5479"\w* \w at|strong="G1161"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w bridegroom|strong="G3566"\w*'\w s|strong="G2192"\w* \w voice|strong="G5456"\w*. \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w my|strong="G1699"\w* \w joy|strong="G5479"\w* \w has|strong="G2192"\w* \w been|strong="G1510"\w* \w fulfilled|strong="G4137"\w*.
\v 30 \w He|strong="G1161"\w* \w must|strong="G1163"\w* increase, \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w must|strong="G1163"\w* \w decrease|strong="G1642"\w*.\f + \fr 3:30 \ft Now there we have an excellent example to follow; all of us should have the same attitude—“He must increase, but I must decrease”.\f*
\p 
\v 31 “\w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w comes|strong="G2064"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w Above|strong="G1883"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w above|strong="G1883"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w*; \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w earth|strong="G1093"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w earthly|strong="G1093"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w speaks|strong="G2980"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w earth|strong="G1093"\w*. \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w comes|strong="G2064"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w Heaven|strong="G3772"\w*\f + \fr 3:31 \ft “From Above” = “from Heaven”. John is talking about Jesus.\f* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w above|strong="G1883"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w*.
\v 32 \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w what|strong="G3739"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w has|strong="G3739"\w* \w seen|strong="G3708"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* heard \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w testifies|strong="G3140"\w*, \w yet|strong="G2532"\w* \w no|strong="G3762"\w* \w one|strong="G3762"\w* \w receives|strong="G2983"\w* \w His|strong="G2983"\w* \w testimony|strong="G3141"\w*.\f + \fr 3:32 \ft So where did Jesus do this ‘seeing’ and ‘hearing’? In Heaven.\f*
\v 33 \w The|strong="G3588"\w* \w one|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w receives|strong="G2983"\w* \w His|strong="G2983"\w* \w testimony|strong="G3141"\w* certifies \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w true|strong="G3588"\w*.
\v 34 \w For|strong="G1063"\w* \w He|strong="G3739"\w* \w whom|strong="G3739"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w sent|strong="G2316"\w* \w speaks|strong="G2980"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*'s \w words|strong="G4487"\w*, \w because|strong="G1063"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w does|strong="G2316"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w give|strong="G1325"\w* \w the|strong="G1537"\w* \w Spirit|strong="G4151"\w* \w by|strong="G1537"\w* \w measure|strong="G3358"\w*.\f + \fr 3:34 \ft The Text does not have “to Him”, but in the context that is presumably to be understood. To the Son the Father gave the Spirit in full measure, but not to us—at least not in the same sense.\f*
\v 35 \w The|strong="G1722"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* loves \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w has|strong="G3962"\w* \w given|strong="G1325"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w things|strong="G3956"\w* \w into|strong="G1722"\w* \w His|strong="G3956"\w* \w hand|strong="G5495"\w*.\f + \fr 3:35 \ft John obviously had a pretty good understanding of who Jesus was.\f*
\v 36 \w The|strong="G1519"\w* \w one|strong="G3588"\w* \w believing|strong="G4100"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w has|strong="G2192"\w* eternal \w life|strong="G2222"\w*, \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w one|strong="G3588"\w* disobeying\f + \fr 3:36 \ft The Text has “disobeying”, not ‘disbelieving’. ‘Believing into’ has to do with commitment, with identification, with relationship. If you enter into a relationship with the Sovereign of the Universe, He is the \bd Boss\bd*. Either you obey or bad things start to happen to you.\f* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w will|strong="G2316"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w see|strong="G3708"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w Life|strong="G2222"\w*, \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w wrath|strong="G3709"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w will|strong="G2316"\w* \w remain|strong="G3306"\w* \w upon|strong="G1909"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*.”\f + \fr 3:36 \ft There are differing opinions about where the Baptizer's speech ends—the rest would then be a commentary by the author, John. The verbs in the present tense in verse 32 tip the decision in favor of the Baptizer—John would have had to use a past tense. I take it that the Baptizer's speech goes through verse 35, at least. Verse 36 could be an editorial comment by John, but I see no reason in the Text for taking the verse away from the Baptizer. Notice the verb ‘will remain’; the only way out is to obey the Son. (Perhaps 50% of the Greek manuscripts have ‘remains’, instead of “will remain”, which does not change the impact of the statement.)\f*
\c 4
\ms1 Jesus and the Samaritans
\m 
\v 1 \w Now|strong="G2532"\w* \w when|strong="G5613"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w*\f + \fr 4:1 \ft I follow the best line of transmission in reading “Jesus”, rather than ‘the Lord’, albeit with only 21.7% of the Greek manuscripts.\f* \w knew|strong="G1097"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Pharisees|strong="G5330"\w*\f + \fr 4:1 \ft The ‘Judean’ in 3:25-26 was probably a Pharisee.\f* \w had|strong="G2424"\w* \w heard|strong="G1097"\w*, “\w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w making|strong="G4160"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* baptizing \w more|strong="G4119"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w* \w than|strong="G2228"\w* \w John|strong="G2491"\w*”
\v 2 (\w although|strong="G2544"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* Himself \w was|strong="G3588"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* baptizing, \w but|strong="G3588"\w* \w His|strong="G3588"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w*),
\v 3 \w He|strong="G2532"\w* left \w Judea|strong="G2449"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w went|strong="G2532"\w* away \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w Galilee|strong="G1056"\w*.\f + \fr 4:3 \ft This was a tactical withdrawal. I take it that Matthew 4:12 refers to the same withdrawal. Between John 3:36 and 4:1 the Baptizer was imprisoned. If the Pharisees knew something it would not be long before Herod knew it. It was not part of the Plan for Jesus to have to deal with Herod at this juncture.\f*
\p 
\v 4 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w He|strong="G1161"\w* \w needed|strong="G1163"\w* \w to|strong="G1163"\w* \w go|strong="G1330"\w* \w through|strong="G1223"\w* \w Samaria|strong="G4540"\w*;\f + \fr 4:4 \ft He could have gone up the coast and avoided most of the mountains, but He “needed” to go through Samaria. Probably because the Father told Him to—it was harvest time in Sychar.\f*
\v 5 \w so|strong="G3767"\w* \w He|strong="G3739"\w* \w comes|strong="G2064"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w a|strong="G1519"\w* \w city|strong="G4172"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w Samaria|strong="G4540"\w* \w called|strong="G3004"\w* \w Sychar|strong="G4965"\w*, \w near|strong="G4139"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* plot \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w land|strong="G5564"\w* \w that|strong="G3739"\w* \w Jacob|strong="G2384"\w* \w gave|strong="G1325"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w his|strong="G1519"\w* \w son|strong="G5207"\w* \w Joseph|strong="G2501"\w*.\f + \fr 4:5 \ft See Joshua 24:32.\f*
\v 6 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w Jacob|strong="G2384"\w*'s \w well|strong="G4077"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w there|strong="G1563"\w*; \w so|strong="G3779"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w*, \w being|strong="G1510"\w* worn \w out|strong="G1537"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G1537"\w* \w journey|strong="G3597"\w*, \w sat|strong="G2516"\w* \w as|strong="G5613"\w* \w He|strong="G1161"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w by|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G1537"\w* \w well|strong="G4077"\w*. \w It|strong="G1161"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w about|strong="G5613"\w* 6 p.m.\f + \fr 4:6 \ft Since John elsewhere always uses Roman time, I assume that he does so here as well. The Text has “the sixth hour”. Many versions put “noon”, which reflects Jewish time. But the Text says Jesus was worn out, which agrees better with a full day's walk than with a half day's walk. The distance between Salem and Sychar was probably about 35 miles, as the crow flies, but since the whole distance was over accidented terrain, the walking distance would be a good deal more. They had walked some 50 miles in twelve hours. Like the Text says, He was tired! And He was hot and thirsty. John emphasizes that as a human being He felt the full effects of the day.\f*
\s1 The woman
\p 
\v 7 \w A|strong="G1325"\w* \w woman|strong="G1135"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w Samaria|strong="G4540"\w* \w comes|strong="G2064"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* draw \w water|strong="G5204"\w*. \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w her|strong="G1325"\w*, “\w Give|strong="G1325"\w* \w me|strong="G1325"\w* \w a|strong="G1325"\w* \w drink|strong="G4095"\w*.”
\v 8 (\w His|strong="G1519"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w* \w had|strong="G3588"\w* gone \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w town|strong="G4172"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* buy \w food|strong="G5160"\w*.)
\v 9 \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w Samaritan|strong="G4542"\w* \w woman|strong="G1135"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w How|strong="G4459"\w* \w can|strong="G3004"\w* \nd \w you|strong="G4771"\w*\nd*, \w being|strong="G1510"\w* \w a|strong="G1510"\w* \w Jew|strong="G2453"\w*, \w ask|strong="G3004"\w* \w a|strong="G1510"\w* \w drink|strong="G4095"\w* \w from|strong="G3844"\w* \nd \w me|strong="G1473"\w*\nd*, \w being|strong="G1510"\w* \w a|strong="G1510"\w* \w Samaritan|strong="G4542"\w* \w woman|strong="G1135"\w*?” (\w for|strong="G1063"\w* \w Jews|strong="G2453"\w* \w do|strong="G3004"\w* \w not|strong="G1510"\w* associate \w with|strong="G3844"\w* Samaritans).
