\v 34 \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*: “\nd \w My|strong="G1699"\w*\nd* \w food|strong="G1033"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w will|strong="G2307"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w sent|strong="G3992"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w complete|strong="G5048"\w* \w His|strong="G4160"\w* \w work|strong="G2041"\w*.\f + \fr 4:34 \ft The Lord was totally committed to the Father's will and game plan; His daily life revolved around it (it was His ‘food’). In His excitement at seeing the plan for Sychar unfold He forgot His physical hunger.\f*
\v 35 \w Do|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w*, ‘\w There|strong="G2532"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w four|strong="G5072"\w* \w months|strong="G5072"\w* \w before|strong="G4314"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w harvest|strong="G2326"\w* \w comes|strong="G2064"\w*?’ \w Well|strong="G2532"\w* \w I|strong="G2532"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w*, \w Look|strong="G2400"\w*! \w Lift|strong="G1869"\w* \w your|strong="G2532"\w* \w eyes|strong="G3788"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* observe \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w fields|strong="G5561"\w*; \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w white|strong="G3022"\w* \w for|strong="G3754"\w* \w harvest|strong="G2326"\w* \w already|strong="G2235"\w*!
\v 36 \w Now|strong="G2532"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w reaps|strong="G2325"\w* \w receives|strong="G2983"\w* \w pay|strong="G3408"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w gathers|strong="G4863"\w* \w fruit|strong="G2590"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* eternal \w life|strong="G2222"\w*,\f + \fr 4:36 \ft That is what the Text says, “into eternal life”. Surely, Jesus is talking about harvesting souls, gathering them into the Kingdom—when someone is born from Above everyone who participated in the process is glad.\f* \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w both|strong="G2532"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w sows|strong="G4687"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w reaps|strong="G2325"\w* \w may|strong="G2532"\w* \w rejoice|strong="G5463"\w* \w together|strong="G4863"\w*.
\v 37 \w Now|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w saying|strong="G3056"\w*, ‘\w One|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w sower|strong="G4687"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w another|strong="G3588"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* reaper,’ \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w true|strong="G3588"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w*:
\v 38 \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w sent|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w reap|strong="G2325"\w* \w that|strong="G3739"\w* \w for|strong="G1519"\w* \w which|strong="G3739"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w labored|strong="G2872"\w*; \w others|strong="G3588"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w labored|strong="G2872"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w entered|strong="G1525"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w their|strong="G2532"\w* \w labors|strong="G2873"\w*.”\f + \fr 4:38 \ft “I sent you to reap” must refer to activity in the past, so I take it that the Lord is stating a general principle.\f*
\s1 The Samaritans
\p 
\v 39 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w many|strong="G4183"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w Samaritans|strong="G4541"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w city|strong="G4172"\w* \w believed|strong="G4100"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w word|strong="G3056"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w woman|strong="G1135"\w*, \w testifying|strong="G3140"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* “\w He|strong="G1161"\w* \w told|strong="G3004"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w everything|strong="G3956"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w ever|strong="G1519"\w* \w did|strong="G4160"\w*!”
\v 40 \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w when|strong="G5613"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Samaritans|strong="G4541"\w* \w came|strong="G2064"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* urged \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w stay|strong="G3306"\w* \w with|strong="G4314"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*; \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w did|strong="G2532"\w* \w stay|strong="G3306"\w* \w there|strong="G1563"\w* \w two|strong="G1417"\w* \w days|strong="G2250"\w*.
\v 41 \w Many|strong="G4183"\w* \w more|strong="G4119"\w* \w believed|strong="G4100"\w* \w through|strong="G1223"\w* \w His|strong="G1223"\w* own \w word|strong="G3056"\w*,
\v 42 \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w kept|strong="G4100"\w* \w saying|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w woman|strong="G1135"\w*, “\w It|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w not|strong="G1510"\w* \w just|strong="G2532"\w* \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w of|strong="G1223"\w* \w what|strong="G3588"\w* \w you|strong="G3754"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w we|strong="G3754"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w*, \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w we|strong="G3754"\w* ourselves \w have|strong="G2532"\w* heard \it Him\it*,\f + \fr 4:42 \ft As the italics indicate, “Him” is not in the Text; perhaps the addition confuses the picture. What do you suppose the disciples were doing during those two days? I bet the Samaritans were eager to hear all that they could about Jesus, what He had said and done—they kept the disciples busy!\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w we|strong="G3754"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w One|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* truly \w the|strong="G2532"\w* Messiah,\f + \fr 4:42 \ft About 0.5% of the Greek manuscripts, of objectively inferior quality, omit “the Messiah” (as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.).\f* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Savior|strong="G4990"\w* \w of|strong="G1223"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w world|strong="G2889"\w*!”\f + \fr 4:42 \ft All right! They got the message!\f*
\ms1 Jesus in Galilee
\p 
\v 43 \w So|strong="G1161"\w* \w after|strong="G3326"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w two|strong="G1417"\w* \w days|strong="G2250"\w* \w He|strong="G1161"\w* \w departed|strong="G1831"\w* \w from|strong="G3588"\w* \w there|strong="G1161"\w* \w and|strong="G1161"\w* \w went|strong="G1831"\w* \w on|strong="G1519"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w Galilee|strong="G1056"\w*.
\v 44 (\w For|strong="G1063"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w Himself|strong="G2398"\w* \w testified|strong="G3140"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w a|strong="G2192"\w* \w prophet|strong="G4396"\w* \w does|strong="G2192"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w honor|strong="G5092"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w his|strong="G1722"\w* \w own|strong="G2398"\w* \w country|strong="G3968"\w*.)\f + \fr 4:44 \ft I believe that the episode recorded in Luke 4:16-30 took place between verses 43 and 45 here, and verse 44 is an echo of Luke 4:24. From Sychar Jesus went directly to Natsareth, was rejected there, and proceeded to Cana. Verse 45 is a summary statement, after the fact. [Of course He was born in Bethlehem, Judea, but I doubt that He is referring to it as ‘his own country’.]\f*
\v 45 \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w when|strong="G3753"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w came|strong="G2064"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w Galilee|strong="G1056"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Galileans|strong="G1057"\w* \w welcomed|strong="G1209"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, \w having|strong="G2532"\w* \w seen|strong="G3708"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w things|strong="G3956"\w* \w that|strong="G3739"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w did|strong="G4160"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w Jerusalem|strong="G2414"\w*, \w at|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w festival|strong="G1859"\w*; \w for|strong="G1063"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w too|strong="G2532"\w* \w had|strong="G2532"\w* gone \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w festival|strong="G1859"\w*.
\s1 Jesus heals at a distance
\p 
\v 46 \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G1510"\w* \w went|strong="G2064"\w* \w again|strong="G3825"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w Cana|strong="G2580"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w Galilee|strong="G1056"\w*,\f + \fr 4:46 \ft I suspect that He had a brother-in-law living there.\f* \w where|strong="G3699"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w made|strong="G4160"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w water|strong="G5204"\w* \w wine|strong="G3631"\w*. \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w there|strong="G2532"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w certain|strong="G2532"\w* royal official \w whose|strong="G3739"\w* \w son|strong="G5207"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* sick \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w Capernaum|strong="G2584"\w*.
\v 47 \w When|strong="G2532"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w man|strong="G3778"\w* heard \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w had|strong="G2424"\w* \w come|strong="G2240"\w* \w out|strong="G1537"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w Judea|strong="G2449"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w Galilee|strong="G1056"\w*, \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w went|strong="G2597"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w implored|strong="G2065"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w come|strong="G2240"\w* \w down|strong="G2597"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w heal|strong="G2390"\w* \w his|strong="G1519"\w* \w son|strong="G5207"\w*,\f + \fr 4:47 \ft The man was asking Jesus to make an emergency hike of some 25 miles (unless he was mounted and had brought an extra horse for Jesus; but He probably wasn't used to riding). Evidently he figured that the healer had to be physically present.\f* \w for|strong="G1063"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* \w about|strong="G3195"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* die.
\v 48 \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Unless|strong="G1437"\w* \w you|strong="G1437"\w* \w people|strong="G3767"\w* \w see|strong="G3708"\w* \w signs|strong="G4592"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w wonders|strong="G5059"\w* \w you|strong="G1437"\w* \w will|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w*!”\f + \fr 4:48 \ft Again, Jesus is not exactly ‘polite’.\f*
\v 49 \w The|strong="G4314"\w* official \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Sir|strong="G2962"\w*, \w come|strong="G2597"\w* \w down|strong="G2597"\w* \w before|strong="G4250"\w* \w my|strong="G1473"\w* \w child|strong="G3813"\w* dies!”
\v 50 \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Go|strong="G4198"\w*; \w your|strong="G2532"\w* \w son|strong="G5207"\w* \w lives|strong="G2198"\w*.” \w Well|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w man|strong="G3739"\w* \w believed|strong="G4100"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w word|strong="G3056"\w* \w that|strong="G3739"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w spoke|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* off \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w went|strong="G4198"\w*.
\v 51 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w while|strong="G1161"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* still \w going|strong="G2597"\w* \w down|strong="G2597"\w* \w his|strong="G2532"\w* \w slaves|strong="G1401"\w* \w met|strong="G5221"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w reported|strong="G3004"\w* \w saying|strong="G3004"\w*, “\w Your|strong="G2532"\w* \w son|strong="G3816"\w* \w lives|strong="G2198"\w*!”
\v 52 \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w he|strong="G3739"\w* \w inquired|strong="G4441"\w* \w of|strong="G3844"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w hour|strong="G5610"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w which|strong="G3739"\w* \w he|strong="G3739"\w* got \w better|strong="G2866"\w*. \w And|strong="G3767"\w* \w they|strong="G3588"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Yesterday|strong="G5504"\w* \w at|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w seventh|strong="G1442"\w* \w hour|strong="G5610"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w fever|strong="G4446"\w* left \w him|strong="G3588"\w*.”\f + \fr 4:52 \ft It is virtually certain that the official and his slaves used Roman time, in which case the cure took place at 7 p.m. It could not be 7 a.m. because the man would have met his slaves before noon and they would have said ‘today’, not ‘yesterday’ (verse 52). It could not be Jewish time for a similar reason—if Jesus healed at 1 p.m. the man would have met his slaves before sundown and they would have said ‘today’. The man probably walked (unless he was mounted, but at night the horse would be held to a walk) during at least part of the night; the slaves would have started out at dawn; they probably met at a point much closer to Capernaum than to Cana.\f*
\v 53 \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w father|strong="G3962"\w* \w knew|strong="G1097"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* \w at|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* exact \w hour|strong="G5610"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w which|strong="G3739"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w told|strong="G3004"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Your|strong="G3650"\w* \w son|strong="G5207"\w* \w lives|strong="G2198"\w*.” \w Both|strong="G2532"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w himself|strong="G1565"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w his|strong="G1722"\w* \w whole|strong="G3650"\w* \w household|strong="G3614"\w* \w believed|strong="G4100"\w*.
\v 54 \w Again|strong="G3825"\w*, \w coming|strong="G2064"\w* \w out|strong="G1537"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w Judea|strong="G2449"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w Galilee|strong="G1056"\w*, \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w performed|strong="G4160"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w second|strong="G1208"\w* miraculous \w sign|strong="G4592"\w*.\f + \fr 4:54 \ft That is, He healed at a distance, just by His thought. Curiously, He was in Cana for both of them.\f*
\c 5
\ms1 Jesus returns to Jerusalem—Passover, 28 AD
\m 
\v 1 \w After|strong="G3326"\w* \w these|strong="G3778"\w* \w things|strong="G3778"\w* \w there|strong="G2532"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w*\f + \fr 5:1 \ft The manuscript evidence is badly divided here, between ‘\nd the\nd* feast’ and ‘\nd a\nd* feast’—I take it that the best evidence is on the side of the definite article. In that event the feast was the Passover (with the other alternative it could still be the Passover), the second during Christ's public ministry; one and a half years are behind Him and there are two to go. For events between the first two Passovers see Mark 1:14-2:17, Luke 4:14-5:39 and Matthew 4:12-8:4.\f* \w feast|strong="G1859"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jews|strong="G2453"\w*, \w so|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w went|strong="G2424"\w* \w up|strong="G1519"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w Jerusalem|strong="G2414"\w*.
\s1 The pool of Bethesda
\p 
\v 2 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w Jerusalem|strong="G2414"\w*, \w by|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Sheep|strong="G4262"\w* Gate, \w there|strong="G1161"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w a|strong="G2192"\w* \w pool|strong="G2861"\w* \w called|strong="G3004"\w* Bethesda,\f + \fr 5:2 \ft Fully 99% of the Greek manuscripts read the familiar ‘Bethesda’, and this name is attested by the 1\sup st\sup* century Copper Scroll from Qumran. The so-called ‘critical text’ (UBS and N-A) serves up the pitiful ‘Bethzatha’, following just five Greek manuscripts (as in TEV, RSV, Jer., etc.). The UBS editors have introduced an historical error into their text on the flimsiest of evidence, even going against their favorites, 𝕻\sup 75\sup* and B.\f* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w Hebrew|strong="G1447"\w*, \w which|strong="G3588"\w* \w has|strong="G2192"\w* \w five|strong="G4002"\w* \w porches|strong="G4745"\w*.\f + \fr 5:2 \ft The pool is a rectangle (it is still there), so it has four sides—so where was the fifth porch? Across the middle, dividing the pool into two smaller ones. Instead of ‘porch’ one could use ‘portico’, ‘cloister’, ‘colonnade’—a \nd covered\nd* walkway.\f*
\v 3 \w In|strong="G1722"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w* \w a|strong="G1722"\w* large \w number|strong="G4128"\w* \w of|strong="G1722"\w* \w sick|strong="G2621"\w* \w people|strong="G4128"\w* \w were|strong="G3588"\w* \w lying|strong="G2621"\w*—\w blind|strong="G5185"\w*, \w lame|strong="G5560"\w*, paralyzed—waiting \w for|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* moving \w of|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* water;
\v 4 because an angel would go down from time to time into the pool and stir up the water\f + \fr 5:4 \ft The angel, whether good or bad, would presumably be invisible to the people, so this information must have been revealed to John.\f*—then the first one to get in after the stirring of the water became well of whatever disease that was holding him.\f + \fr 5:4 \ft About 0.8% of the Greek manuscripts, of objectively inferior quality, omit the last clause of verse 3 and all of verse 4 (as in NIV, NASB, LB, [TEV], etc.). But obviously all those people would not stay there (in discomfort) day in and day out, year in and year out, if nothing was happening. Obviously people got healed (from serious diseases), and verse 7 makes clear that it had to do with the stirring of the water—so why didn't those manuscripts omit verse 7 as well? The UBS editions do us a considerable disservice by following a very small minority of manuscripts (perhaps 2%) and making the angel ‘of the Lord’. Since angels can be good or fallen, it seems most likely to me that the angel involved was fallen. A capricious, occasional healing condemned all those people to added suffering (being at the pool instead of the comfort of home), including the frustration and despair of those who never made it (like the man Jesus healed). A sadistic procedure is just like Satan.\f*
\s2 The man selected for healing
\p 
\v 5 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w there|strong="G1563"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w a|strong="G2192"\w* \w certain|strong="G5100"\w* \w man|strong="G5100"\w* \w there|strong="G1563"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w had|strong="G2192"\w* \w been|strong="G1510"\w* sick \w for|strong="G1161"\w* 38 \w years|strong="G2094"\w*.\f + \fr 5:5 \ft Wow!\f*
\v 6 \w Seeing|strong="G3708"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w man|strong="G3778"\w* \w lying|strong="G2621"\w* \w there|strong="G2532"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w knowing|strong="G1097"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w had|strong="G2192"\w* \w already|strong="G2235"\w* \w been|strong="G1096"\w* \w sick|strong="G2621"\w* \w a|strong="G2192"\w* \w long|strong="G4183"\w* \w time|strong="G5550"\w*, \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Do|strong="G1096"\w* \w you|strong="G3754"\w* \w want|strong="G2309"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w get|strong="G1096"\w* \w well|strong="G2532"\w*?”
\v 7 \w The|strong="G1722"\w* sick \w man|strong="G3739"\w* answered \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Sir|strong="G2962"\w*, \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w no|strong="G3756"\w* \w man|strong="G3739"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* throw\f + \fr 5:7 \ft That is right, “throw”. Hey, where a split second could make the difference no one is going to stand on ceremony—when the water started to move there would be a mad scramble; people would be thrown at the water, literally. (The demons would really enjoy themselves, seeing ‘the image of God’ humiliated in that way.)\f* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w pool|strong="G2861"\w* \w when|strong="G3752"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w water|strong="G5204"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w stirred|strong="G5015"\w* \w up|strong="G1519"\w*, \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w while|strong="G1722"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1473"\w* \w coming|strong="G2064"\w* \w another|strong="G3739"\w* gets \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w before|strong="G4253"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*.”
