\v 11 \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w The|strong="G2532"\w* \w one|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w made|strong="G4160"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w well|strong="G2532"\w*—\nd \w He|strong="G2532"\w*\nd* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*, ‘Pick \w up|strong="G2532"\w* \w your|strong="G2532"\w* \w pallet|strong="G2895"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w walk|strong="G4043"\w*.’ ”
\v 12 \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w asked|strong="G2065"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\nd \w Who|strong="G5101"\w*\nd* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w man|strong="G5101"\w* \w who|strong="G5101"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w*, ‘Pick \w up|strong="G2532"\w* \w your|strong="G2532"\w* pallet \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w walk|strong="G4043"\w*’?”
\v 13 \w But|strong="G1161"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w man|strong="G3756"\w* \w who|strong="G5101"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w cured|strong="G2390"\w* \w did|strong="G1492"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w who|strong="G5101"\w* \w it|strong="G1161"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w*, \w because|strong="G1063"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w had|strong="G2424"\w* disappeared, \w there|strong="G1161"\w* \w being|strong="G1510"\w* \w a|strong="G1722"\w* \w crowd|strong="G3793"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w place|strong="G5117"\w*.\f + \fr 5:13 \ft Let's stop and think about what Jesus did here. There were probably hundreds of sick people there—why did He only heal \bd one\bd* of them? And why did He disappear into the crowd before the man could find out who He was? And why did He do this on a Sabbath? I think it was all deliberate—He wanted to provoke the Jews. He chose a Sabbath; He chose a man who had a pallet, but who had no slave or other helper; He commanded (yes, commanded) the man to carry the pallet; He got out of the way so the Jews would have the man to themselves. In this way He set up a confrontation, as we will see below. [In passing we may note that if ever there was a ‘divine healer’ it was the Lord Jesus, and yet He did not empty out this ‘hospital’. Maybe divine healers aren't supposed to empty hospitals.]\f*
\p 
\v 14 \w After|strong="G3326"\w* \w these|strong="G3778"\w* \w things|strong="G3778"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w found|strong="G2147"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w temple|strong="G2413"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w See|strong="G3708"\w*, \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w well|strong="G2532"\w*. Don'\w t|strong="G3588"\w* sin \w any|strong="G5100"\w* \w more|strong="G3371"\w*, \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w something|strong="G5100"\w* \w worse|strong="G5501"\w* doesn'\w t|strong="G3588"\w* \w happen|strong="G1096"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w*.”\f + \fr 5:14 \ft The Lord seems to be implying that the former sickness was the result of sin. But he had been sick for 38 years, so he had paid a heavy price!\f*
\v 15 \w The|strong="G2532"\w* \w man|strong="G4160"\w* \w went|strong="G2424"\w* off \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w told|strong="G3004"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jews|strong="G2453"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w had|strong="G2424"\w* \w made|strong="G4160"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w well|strong="G2532"\w*.
\s2 The Jews want to kill Jesus
\p 
\v 16 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w of|strong="G1223"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Jews|strong="G2453"\w* began \w persecuting|strong="G1377"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* trying \w to|strong="G2532"\w* kill \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*,\f + \fr 5:16 \ft Less than 3% of the Greek manuscripts, of inferior quality, omit “and trying to kill Him” (as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.).\f* \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* \w doing|strong="G4160"\w* \w these|strong="G3778"\w* \w things|strong="G3778"\w* \w on|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Sabbath|strong="G4521"\w*.\f + \fr 5:16 \ft The last recorded events before John 5:1 are in Luke 5:12-39. The healing of the paralytic had impressed the Jews, but then Jesus immediately went and ate with publicans; and verses 36-39 were against what the Jews represented. Here in John Jesus challenges their authority over the Sabbath.\f*
\v 17 \w But|strong="G1161"\w* Jesus answered \w them|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Until|strong="G2193"\w* \w now|strong="G1161"\w*, \w my|strong="G1473"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* \w works|strong="G2038"\w*, \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w also|strong="G2504"\w* \w work|strong="G2038"\w*.”\f + \fr 5:17 \ft Not only does Jesus not run and hide, He ‘ups the ante’—He claims to be God, as the Jews understood perfectly well (and which in their mind called for the death penalty, since they were not prepared to acknowledge that claim).\f*
\v 18 \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w of|strong="G1223"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w wanted|strong="G2212"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* kill \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w all|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w more|strong="G3123"\w*, \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w only|strong="G3440"\w* \w breaking|strong="G3089"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Sabbath|strong="G4521"\w* \w but|strong="G2532"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* \w even|strong="G2532"\w* \w saying|strong="G3004"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* \w His|strong="G1438"\w* \w own|strong="G2398"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w*, \w making|strong="G4160"\w* \w Himself|strong="G1438"\w* \w equal|strong="G2470"\w* \w with|strong="G1223"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*!
\s1 Jesus addresses the Jews
\s2 He affirms His equality with the Father
\p 
\v 19 \w Then|strong="G3767"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*: “Most assuredly \w I|strong="G3739"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w able|strong="G1410"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w* \w anything|strong="G5100"\w* \w from|strong="G2532"\w* \w Himself|strong="G1438"\w*, \w except|strong="G1437"\w* \w something|strong="G5100"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* sees \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* \w doing|strong="G4160"\w*; \w because|strong="G1063"\w* \w whatever|strong="G3739"\w* \w things|strong="G3778"\w* \nd \w He|strong="G2532"\w*\nd* \w does|strong="G4160"\w*, precisely \w these|strong="G3778"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w does|strong="G4160"\w*.\f + \fr 5:19 \ft I find this statement to be amazing, revealing and challenging. Jesus only did what He saw the Father doing; so how about us? I would say that my main ‘ministry’ problem is that I often don't know what the Father is doing, and so I waste a lot of time and effort.\f*
\v 20 \w For|strong="G1063"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* \w loves|strong="G5368"\w*\f + \fr 5:20 \ft To my surprise the verb here is φιλεω, not αγαπαω—the Father is emotionally attached to the Son. Well, since we have emotions God must have had them first. God affirms that He has soul (Isaiah 42:1, Matthew 12:18, Hebrews 10:38).\f* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w shows|strong="G1166"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w everything|strong="G3956"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* Himself \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w doing|strong="G4160"\w*; \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w will|strong="G2532"\w* \w show|strong="G1166"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \nd \w greater|strong="G3173"\w*\nd* \w works|strong="G2041"\w* \w than|strong="G3173"\w* \w these|strong="G3778"\w*, \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w may|strong="G2532"\w* \w marvel|strong="G2296"\w*.
\v 21 \w Now|strong="G2532"\w* \w just|strong="G5618"\w* \w as|strong="G5618"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* \w raises|strong="G1453"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w dead|strong="G3498"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w gives|strong="G2227"\w* \w life|strong="G2227"\w*, \w just|strong="G5618"\w* \w so|strong="G3779"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w gives|strong="G2227"\w* \w life|strong="G2227"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w whom|strong="G3739"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w wishes|strong="G2309"\w*.
\v 22 \w In|strong="G3956"\w* fact \w the|strong="G3956"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* \w does|strong="G3761"\w* \w not|strong="G3761"\w* \w judge|strong="G2919"\w* \w anyone|strong="G3762"\w* \w but|strong="G1063"\w* \w has|strong="G3962"\w* committed \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w the|strong="G3956"\w* \w judging|strong="G2919"\w* \w to|strong="G1325"\w* \w the|strong="G3956"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w*,\f + \fr 5:22 \ft I suppose this means that it will be the Son who sits on the ‘great white throne’ (Revelation 20:11).\f*
\v 23 \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w will|strong="G3956"\w* \w honor|strong="G5091"\w* \w the|strong="G3956"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w just|strong="G2531"\w* \w as|strong="G2531"\w* \w they|strong="G3588"\w* \w honor|strong="G5091"\w* \w the|strong="G3956"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w*.\f + \fr 5:23 \ft Of course someone who does not honor the Father will not honor the Son either.\f* \w Whoever|strong="G3956"\w* \w does|strong="G5091"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w honor|strong="G5091"\w* \w the|strong="G3956"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w does|strong="G5091"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w honor|strong="G5091"\w* \w the|strong="G3956"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w sent|strong="G3992"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*.\f + \fr 5:23 \ft I take it that the Lord Jesus is saying that monotheistic people (Jews, Muslims) who claim to honor the Father, but do not honor the Son, are not really doing so. (Perhaps that would not apply to those who have never heard about Jesus.)\f*
\s2 The Son is the just Judge
\p 
\v 24 “\w Most|strong="G1537"\w* assuredly \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w one|strong="G3588"\w* listening\f + \fr 5:24 \ft Most versions render ‘hear’ instead of ‘listen’, both here and in the next verse, but from the context it seems clear that Jesus is not talking about sound striking the eardrum; He is talking about acting on the basis of what is heard.\f* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w my|strong="G1473"\w* \w word|strong="G3056"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w believing|strong="G4100"\w* \w on|strong="G1519"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w sent|strong="G3992"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w has|strong="G2192"\w* eternal \w life|strong="G2222"\w*; \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w will|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w go|strong="G2064"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* judging \w but|strong="G2532"\w* \w has|strong="G2192"\w* moved \w out|strong="G1537"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w death|strong="G2288"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Life|strong="G2222"\w*.\f + \fr 5:24 \ft “The death” refers to Satan's kingdom; “the life” refers to Christ's kingdom (and they are the only alternatives in this world).\f*
\p 
\v 25 “\w Most|strong="G2316"\w* assuredly \w I|strong="G2532"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w time|strong="G5610"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w coming|strong="G2064"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w now|strong="G3568"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w*, \w when|strong="G3753"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w dead|strong="G3498"\w* \w will|strong="G2316"\w* \w hear|strong="G5456"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w voice|strong="G5456"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \nd \w the|strong="G2532"\w*\nd* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* listen \w will|strong="G2316"\w* \w live|strong="G2198"\w*.\f + \fr 5:25 \ft It seems clear that the picture here is different from that in verses 28-29. Here Jesus says “now is”, so He is not talking about future judgment; so the dead here are spiritually dead, and those who listen to Him receive spiritual life. In verse 28 the reference is to the physically dead, who are raised to face the final judgment.\f*
\v 26 \w Because|strong="G1063"\w* \w just|strong="G5618"\w* \w as|strong="G5618"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* \w has|strong="G2192"\w* \w life|strong="G2222"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w Himself|strong="G1438"\w*, \w just|strong="G5618"\w* \w so|strong="G3779"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w gave|strong="G1325"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w life|strong="G2222"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w Himself|strong="G1438"\w*;
\v 27 \w furthermore|strong="G2532"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w gave|strong="G1325"\w* \w Him|strong="G1325"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w authority|strong="G1849"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w pass|strong="G4160"\w* \w judgment|strong="G2920"\w*, \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w Man|strong="G5207"\w*.\f + \fr 5:27 \ft We as human beings will be judged by another human being, someone who knows what it's like. There is no definite article with either “Son” or “Man”, so this is not the title He normally used.\f*
\v 28 \w Do|strong="G3361"\w* \w not|strong="G3361"\w* \w marvel|strong="G2296"\w* \w at|strong="G1722"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w*, \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w a|strong="G1722"\w* \w time|strong="G5610"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w coming|strong="G2064"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w which|strong="G3739"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w graves|strong="G3419"\w* \w will|strong="G3739"\w* \w hear|strong="G5456"\w* \w His|strong="G3956"\w* \w voice|strong="G5456"\w*
\v 29 \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w will|strong="G2532"\w* \w come|strong="G1607"\w* \w out|strong="G1607"\w*—\w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w did|strong="G4160"\w* \w good|strong="G3588"\w* \w things|strong="G3588"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* resurrection \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w life|strong="G2222"\w*,\f + \fr 5:29 \ft Notice again the emphasis on \nd doing\nd*, because what you do reflects what you \bd really\bd* believe, and what you really believe is what you are—and you cannot kid God. “All those in the graves” means everyone who has died; all will be raised, and all must face the final Accounting.\f* \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w practiced|strong="G4238"\w* \w evil|strong="G5337"\w* \w things|strong="G3588"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* resurrection \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w condemnation|strong="G2920"\w*.
\v 30 \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w able|strong="G1410"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w* \w anything|strong="G3762"\w* \w from|strong="G2532"\w* \w myself|strong="G1683"\w*. \w As|strong="G2531"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* hear, \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w judge|strong="G2919"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w my|strong="G1699"\w* \w judging|strong="G2919"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w just|strong="G2531"\w*, \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w seek|strong="G2212"\w* \w my|strong="G1699"\w* \w own|strong="G1699"\w* \w will|strong="G2307"\w* \w but|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w will|strong="G2307"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* Father \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w sent|strong="G3992"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*.
\s2 Four witnesses to Jesus
\p 
\v 31 “\w If|strong="G1437"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w testify|strong="G3140"\w* \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w myself|strong="G1683"\w*, \w my|strong="G1473"\w* \w testimony|strong="G3141"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* valid.\f + \fr 5:31 \ft According to the Law at least two witnesses were required, so if Jesus had only His own word it would not be enough, would not be valid (even though He told the truth).\f*
\v 32 \w There|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w another|strong="G3739"\w* \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w testifies|strong="G3140"\w* \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w testimony|strong="G3141"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w gives|strong="G3140"\w* \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w true|strong="G3588"\w*.\f + \fr 5:32 \ft I take it that this witness must be the Father, since in verse 34 Jesus discounts John the Baptizer.\f*
\v 33 \w You|strong="G5210"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w sent|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w John|strong="G2491"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w has|strong="G2532"\w* \w testified|strong="G3140"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* truth.
\v 34 \w Yet|strong="G1161"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w do|strong="G3004"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w accept|strong="G2983"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w testimony|strong="G3141"\w* \w from|strong="G3844"\w* \w a|strong="G2983"\w* \w man|strong="G3778"\w*; \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w these|strong="G3778"\w* \w things|strong="G3778"\w* \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w may|strong="G2443"\w* \w be|strong="G3756"\w* \w saved|strong="G4982"\w*.\f + \fr 5:34 \ft Since Jesus has three supernatural witnesses—the Father, His own works and the Scriptures—He does not need John. I do not believe Jesus was angry with John or otherwise dissatisfied with his testimony; it is just that the Jews had already rejected John's testimony about Jesus (as they had rejected Jesus Himself). As He says, He would like for them to turn around and be saved, so He organizes His argument in that attempt.\f*
\v 35 \w That|strong="G3588"\w* \w man|strong="G1565"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w burning|strong="G2545"\w*, \w shining|strong="G5316"\w* \w lamp|strong="G3088"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w for|strong="G4314"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w time|strong="G5610"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w were|strong="G1510"\w* \w willing|strong="G2309"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* glad \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w his|strong="G1722"\w* \w light|strong="G5457"\w*.
\v 36 \w But|strong="G1161"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w a|strong="G2192"\w* \w greater|strong="G3173"\w* \w testimony|strong="G3141"\w* \w than|strong="G3173"\w* \w John|strong="G2491"\w*'\w s|strong="G2192"\w*, \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w works|strong="G2041"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* \w gave|strong="G1325"\w* \w me|strong="G1325"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w complete|strong="G5048"\w*—\w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w very|strong="G3588"\w* \w works|strong="G2041"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1473"\w* \w doing|strong="G4160"\w*—\w they|strong="G1161"\w* \w testify|strong="G3140"\w* \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w me|strong="G1325"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* \w has|strong="G2192"\w* sent \w me|strong="G1325"\w*.\f + \fr 5:36 \ft Nicodemus recognized this.\f*
\p 
\v 37 “Further, \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w sent|strong="G3992"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w has|strong="G3962"\w* \w Himself|strong="G1565"\w* \w testified|strong="G3140"\w* \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*. \w You|strong="G3708"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w neither|strong="G3777"\w* heard \w His|strong="G4012"\w* \w voice|strong="G5456"\w* \w nor|strong="G3777"\w* \w seen|strong="G3708"\w* \w His|strong="G4012"\w* \w form|strong="G1491"\w* \w at|strong="G4012"\w* \w any|strong="G4455"\w* \w time|strong="G4455"\w*.
\v 38 \w Nor|strong="G2532"\w* \w do|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w His|strong="G1722"\w* \w word|strong="G3056"\w* \w abiding|strong="G3306"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*,\f + \fr 5:38 \ft The Lord declares their spiritual bankruptcy. For a religious leader to have never heard God's voice is pretty poor, but much worse is to study God's Word without its ever finding a place in your heart.\f* \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w do|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w* \w on|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w very|strong="G2532"\w* \w one|strong="G3739"\w* \w whom|strong="G3739"\w* \nd \w He|strong="G2532"\w*\nd* \w sent|strong="G2532"\w*.
\v 39 \w You|strong="G5210"\w* examine \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Scriptures|strong="G1124"\w* \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w think|strong="G1380"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* eternal \w life|strong="G2222"\w*, \w yet|strong="G2532"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w very|strong="G2532"\w* \w ones|strong="G3748"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w testify|strong="G3140"\w* \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*.
\v 40 \w But|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G2532"\w* \w are|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w willing|strong="G2309"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w come|strong="G2064"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w you|strong="G2532"\w* \w may|strong="G2532"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w life|strong="G2222"\w*.\f + \fr 5:40 \ft Jesus had proved that He was the Messiah, but He threatened everything that they stood for.\f*
\s2 The Jews are accused by Moses
\p 
\v 41 “\w I|strong="G2983"\w* \w do|strong="G2983"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w accept|strong="G2983"\w* \w glory|strong="G1391"\w* \w from|strong="G3844"\w* \w people|strong="G2983"\w*.
\v 42 \w Rather|strong="G3756"\w* \w I|strong="G3754"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w come|strong="G3756"\w* \w to|strong="G1722"\w* \w know|strong="G1097"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*,\f + \fr 5:42 \ft That is what the Text says, “I have come to know”—presumably He is referring to knowledge gained by observation; they have clearly demonstrated in His presence that in fact they do not have God's love.\f* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w do|strong="G2192"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* love \w of|strong="G2316"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*.
\v 43 \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w come|strong="G2064"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w my|strong="G1722"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w*'s \w name|strong="G3686"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G1437"\w* \w do|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w receive|strong="G2983"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*; \w should|strong="G3588"\w* \w another|strong="G3588"\w* \w come|strong="G2064"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w his|strong="G1722"\w* \w own|strong="G2398"\w* \w name|strong="G3686"\w*, \nd \w him|strong="G3588"\w*\nd* \w you|strong="G1437"\w* \w will|strong="G2532"\w* \w receive|strong="G2983"\w*.\f + \fr 5:43 \ft Might this be a prophetic reference to the Antichrist?\f*
\v 44 \w How|strong="G4459"\w* \nd \w can|strong="G1410"\w*\nd* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w*, \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w receive|strong="G2983"\w* \w glory|strong="G1391"\w* \w from|strong="G3844"\w* \w men|strong="G3588"\w*\f + \fr 5:44 \ft Here I follow what I consider to be by far the best line of transmission, although attested by less than 30% of the Greek manuscripts.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w do|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w seek|strong="G2212"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w glory|strong="G1391"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w comes|strong="G2532"\w* \w from|strong="G3844"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w only|strong="G3441"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*?\f + \fr 5:44 \ft This is serious! Apparently one's attitude toward glory affects his ability to believe. If the approval of people is more important to you than the approval of God, you probably will not believe into Jesus.\f*
\p 
\v 45 “\w Do|strong="G1380"\w* \w not|strong="G3361"\w* \w suppose|strong="G1380"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* \w accuse|strong="G2723"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w before|strong="G4314"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w*. \bd \w Moses|strong="G3475"\w*\bd* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w one|strong="G3739"\w* \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w accuses|strong="G2723"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, \w on|strong="G1519"\w* \w whom|strong="G3739"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w have|strong="G1473"\w* \w set|strong="G1679"\w* \w your|strong="G3588"\w* \w hope|strong="G1679"\w*.
\v 46 \w Because|strong="G1063"\w* \w if|strong="G1487"\w* \w you|strong="G1487"\w* \it really\it* \w believed|strong="G4100"\w* \w Moses|strong="G3475"\w* \w you|strong="G1487"\w* \w would|strong="G4100"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*, \w because|strong="G1063"\w* \w he|strong="G1565"\w* \w wrote|strong="G1125"\w* \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*.
\v 47 \w But|strong="G1161"\w* \w since|strong="G1161"\w* \w you|strong="G1487"\w* \w do|strong="G4100"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w* \w his|strong="G1565"\w* \nd \w writings|strong="G1121"\w*\nd*, \w how|strong="G4459"\w* \w will|strong="G4100"\w* \w you|strong="G1487"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w* \w my|strong="G1699"\w* \w sayings|strong="G4487"\w*?”\f + \fr 5:47 \ft The Lord is affirming the inspiration and authority of Moses' \nd writings\nd*; in effect He places them on a level with His own word, for which He claims eternal authority (Luke 21:33).\f*
\c 6
\ms1 Jesus is back in Galilee\f + \fr 6:0 \ft Almost a whole year has elapsed between chapters 5 and 6 here. For the events that transpired during that period see Luke 6:1-9:10, Mark 2:23-6:31 and the corresponding accounts in Matthew.\f*
\m 
\v 1 \w After|strong="G3326"\w* \w these|strong="G3778"\w* \w things|strong="G3778"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w went|strong="G2424"\w* \w over|strong="G4008"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w Sea|strong="G2281"\w* \w of|strong="G2424"\w* \w Galilee|strong="G1056"\w*, \w or|strong="G3588"\w* \w Tiberias|strong="G5085"\w*.\f + \fr 6:1 \ft From the parallel accounts it appears that He embarked at Capernaum. (Matthew informs us that He had just heard of the Baptizer's ignominious death and wanted to get away—perhaps to grieve and assimilate the news.) From John 6:23 we learn that the destination was near Tiberias. Capernaum and Tiberias are both on the western side of the Sea of Galilee, but there is a large bay between them; so they went over 6-8 miles of water.\f*
\v 2 \w And|strong="G1161"\w* \w a|strong="G1909"\w* huge \w crowd|strong="G3793"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* following \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w they|strong="G1161"\w* \w had|strong="G3739"\w* \w seen|strong="G3708"\w* \w His|strong="G1909"\w* \w signs|strong="G4592"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w He|strong="G1161"\w* \w kept|strong="G4160"\w* \w performing|strong="G4160"\w* \w on|strong="G1909"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* sick.\f + \fr 6:2 \ft The crowd was not about to let Jesus get away. Mark makes clear that they ran along the shore—the faster runners stayed even with the boat and were waiting on the shore when the boat put in. The others were spread out behind for several miles (like in a marathon) and kept arriving. Any late starters would see the stragglers and could easily follow the action. Apparently He immediately started to heal the sick and went on to teach (Matthew 14:14, Mark 6:34). But just where was it? John says it was near Tiberias, but Luke 9:10 says it was “a deserted place belonging to a town called Bethsaida”. [Less than 1% of the Greek manuscripts, of objectively inferior quality, have “into a town called Bethsaida” (as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.), which makes Luke contradict himself (verse 12 says it was a deserted place) as well as the parallel accounts.] I assume that the place was indeed near Tiberias but did indeed belong to Bethsaida—either it had been deeded to the town somehow or the family that owned it was based in Bethsaida. Any near neighbors could not use it, so it was basically untouched—a great place for a picnic.\f*
\v 3 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w went|strong="G2424"\w* \w up|strong="G1519"\w* \w on|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w mountain|strong="G3735"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w sat|strong="G2521"\w* \w down|strong="G2521"\w* \w there|strong="G1563"\w* \w with|strong="G3326"\w* \w His|strong="G1519"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w*.\f + \fr 6:3 \ft Comparing the other accounts, I take it that they had already spent quite a bit of time on the beach, and the afternoon was wearing away. Since verse 6 says He knew what He was going to do, I assume it was a deliberate move to get the crowd up where there was grass so they could sit down in relative comfort.\f*
\v 4 (\w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w Passover|strong="G3957"\w*, \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w feast|strong="G1859"\w* \w of|strong="G3588"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w Jews|strong="G2453"\w*, \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w near|strong="G1451"\w*.)\f + \fr 6:4 \ft I frankly do not see what connection this information has with the story, but it does give us a time frame.\f*
\s1 Food for 15,000\f + \fr 6:5 \ft Why 15,000? Well, Matthew 14:21 says plainly that there were about 5,000 men \nd besides women and children\nd*. In any crowd what is there usually most of? Since the context was not one of war (where there would be mostly men) I imagine there were at least 15,000 people there (like mothers with sick children).\f*
\p 
\v 5 \w Then|strong="G3767"\w*, raising \w His|strong="G2532"\w* \w eyes|strong="G3788"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* observing \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* huge \w crowd|strong="G3793"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* \w coming|strong="G2064"\w* \w toward|strong="G4314"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w Philip|strong="G5376"\w*, “\w Where|strong="G4159"\w* \w shall|strong="G2532"\w* \w we|strong="G3754"\w* buy bread \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w these|strong="G3778"\w* folks \w may|strong="G2532"\w* \w eat|strong="G2068"\w*?”\f + \fr 6:5 \ft According to the other three accounts, the disciples had already suggested to Jesus that He send the people away to the surrounding towns to buy food. But let's stop and think. How many bread stores would a village have, and how much bread would a store still have on hand at 5 p.m.? If they could have gone to every store within a radius of 30 miles, I doubt that they would have found even 10,000 loaves available. The Lord's question shows that their suggestion was really a cop-out.\f*
\v 6 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w He|strong="G1161"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w test|strong="G3985"\w* \w him|strong="G4160"\w*, \w for|strong="G1063"\w* \w He|strong="G1161"\w* Himself \w knew|strong="G1492"\w* \w what|strong="G5101"\w* \w He|strong="G1161"\w* \w was|strong="G3778"\w* \w about|strong="G3195"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w*.
\v 7 \w Philip|strong="G5376"\w* answered \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Two|strong="G1250"\w* \w hundred|strong="G1250"\w* \w denarii|strong="G1220"\w* worth \w of|strong="G5100"\w* bread\f + \fr 6:7 \ft How much bread can you buy with the wages for 200 days of manual labor? Probably an awful lot of it. But the crowd was so huge that Philip figured that even that much would not do it. [If a day's wage would buy 50 small loaves, for instance, that would make 10,000 loaves—more people than bread.]\f* \w would|strong="G5100"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w be|strong="G3756"\w* enough \w for|strong="G2443"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*, \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w each|strong="G1538"\w* \w of|strong="G5100"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w* \w could|strong="G3588"\w* \w receive|strong="G2983"\w* \w a|strong="G2983"\w* \w little|strong="G1024"\w*.”
\v 8 \w One|strong="G1520"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w His|strong="G3588"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w*, Andrew, \w Simon|strong="G4613"\w* \w Peter|strong="G4074"\w*'s brother, \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*,
\v 9 “\w There|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w a|strong="G2192"\w* little boy \w here|strong="G5602"\w* \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w has|strong="G2192"\w* \w five|strong="G4002"\w* loaves \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w barley|strong="G2916"\w* bread \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w two|strong="G1417"\w* \w small|strong="G1417"\w* \w fish|strong="G3795"\w*, \w but|strong="G2532"\w* \w what|strong="G5101"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w for|strong="G1519"\w* \w so|strong="G2532"\w* \w many|strong="G5118"\w*?”\f + \fr 6:9 \ft I think it must be understood that the boy handed them over willingly, so he participated in the miracle. We also must give to God willingly, and when we do we participate in the results.\f*
\p 
\v 10 \w Then|strong="G3767"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w*, “\w Make|strong="G4160"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w people|strong="G1510"\w* recline.” \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w there|strong="G1161"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* plenty \w of|strong="G1722"\w* \w grass|strong="G5528"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w place|strong="G5117"\w*; \w so|strong="G3767"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w men|strong="G3588"\w* reclined, \w about|strong="G5613"\w* \w five|strong="G4000"\w* \w thousand|strong="G4000"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* number.
\v 11 \w Then|strong="G3767"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w took|strong="G2983"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* loaves, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w having|strong="G2532"\w* \w given|strong="G1325"\w* \w thanks|strong="G2168"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w distributed|strong="G1239"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3588"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3588"\w*\f + \fr 6:11 \ft Perhaps 3% of the Greek manuscripts, of inferior quality, omit the reference to the disciples here and have Jesus distributing directly to the crowd (as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.), making John contradict the other three Gospels.\f* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w were|strong="G3588"\w* reclining; \w so|strong="G3767"\w* \w too|strong="G2532"\w* \w with|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w fish|strong="G3795"\w*, \w as|strong="G3745"\w* \w much|strong="G3745"\w* \w as|strong="G3745"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w wanted|strong="G2309"\w*.
\v 12 \w So|strong="G2443"\w* \w when|strong="G1161"\w* \w they|strong="G1161"\w* \w were|strong="G3588"\w* full \w He|strong="G1161"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w His|strong="G5613"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w*, “Collect \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w leftover|strong="G4052"\w* \w fragments|strong="G2801"\w* \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w nothing|strong="G3361"\w* \w be|strong="G3361"\w* wasted.”\f + \fr 6:12 \ft Notice the care that nothing be wasted. A common human reaction would be, ‘easy come, easy go’—since Jesus can make more any time He wants, why worry. But no, the Lord does not look at it that way.\f*
\v 13 \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* collected \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w filled|strong="G1072"\w* \w twelve|strong="G1427"\w* \w baskets|strong="G2894"\w*\f + \fr 6:13 \ft They were large baskets, probably borrowed from the fishing boats (see verse 23 below). The disciples probably had help with the collecting; and in any case, they did not keep that food.\f* \w with|strong="G1537"\w* \w fragments|strong="G2801"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w five|strong="G4002"\w* \w barley|strong="G2916"\w* loaves \w that|strong="G3739"\w* \w were|strong="G3588"\w* \w left|strong="G4052"\w* \w over|strong="G1537"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w had|strong="G2532"\w* eaten.
\p 
\v 14 \w Now|strong="G3767"\w* \w then|strong="G3767"\w*, \w having|strong="G3767"\w* \w seen|strong="G3708"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* miraculous \w sign|strong="G4592"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G3004"\w* \w performed|strong="G4160"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w men|strong="G3778"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w*, “\w This|strong="G3778"\w* \w One|strong="G3739"\w* really \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w Prophet|strong="G4396"\w* \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w come|strong="G2064"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w world|strong="G2889"\w*.”
\v 15 \w So|strong="G2443"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w*, \w perceiving|strong="G1097"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w were|strong="G3588"\w* \w about|strong="G3195"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w come|strong="G2064"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w take|strong="G2532"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w by|strong="G2532"\w* force \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w make|strong="G4160"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w king|strong="G3588"\w*,\f + \fr 6:15 \ft Only John records this information, plus what is given from verse 22 on. I take it that at least up to verse 40 Jesus is basically dealing with the ‘king-makers’.\f* \w withdrew|strong="G2424"\w* \w up|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w mountain|strong="G3735"\w* \w again|strong="G3825"\w* \w by|strong="G2532"\w* \w Himself|strong="G3441"\w*, \w alone|strong="G3441"\w*.
\s2 Jesus walks on water
\p 
\v 16 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w as|strong="G5613"\w* \w evening|strong="G3798"\w* \w came|strong="G1096"\w* \w on|strong="G1909"\w* \w His|strong="G1909"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w* \w had|strong="G3588"\w* gone \w down|strong="G2597"\w* \w to|strong="G1909"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w sea|strong="G2281"\w*,
\v 17 \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w getting|strong="G1684"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w boat|strong="G4143"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w started|strong="G1096"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w go|strong="G2064"\w* \w across|strong="G4008"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w sea|strong="G2281"\w* \w toward|strong="G1519"\w* \w Capernaum|strong="G2584"\w*.\f + \fr 6:17 \ft When they started out, the boat would be pointing toward Capernaum/Genesaret/Bethsaida; only as they went on would it become clear that their first destination was Bethsaida (Mark 6:45).\f* \w Well|strong="G2532"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w had|strong="G2424"\w* \w been|strong="G1096"\w* \w dark|strong="G4653"\w* \w for|strong="G1519"\w* \w a|strong="G1096"\w* \w while|strong="G1161"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w had|strong="G2424"\w* \w not|strong="G3768"\w* \w come|strong="G2064"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*.\f + \fr 6:17 \ft This statement puzzles me. The author of this Gospel was in that boat. Did they really expect Jesus to come to them over the water? How? Evidently they did not expect Him to come walking.\f*
\v 18 Further, \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w sea|strong="G2281"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* being agitated \w by|strong="G5037"\w* \w a|strong="G5037"\w* \w strong|strong="G3173"\w* \w wind|strong="G4154"\w* \w blowing|strong="G4154"\w*.
\v 19 \w Then|strong="G3767"\w*, \w after|strong="G1909"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w had|strong="G2424"\w* \w rowed|strong="G1643"\w* \w some|strong="G3588"\w* \w three|strong="G1096"\w* \w or|strong="G2228"\w* \w four|strong="G5613"\w* \w miles|strong="G4712"\w*,\f + \fr 6:19 \ft The Text actually says ‘twenty-five or thirty stadia’. In Matthew 14:24 over 99% of the Greek manuscripts have them “in the middle of the sea”. If you draw a line from Tiberias to Bethsaida (see Mark 6:45) and put an X at four miles you will be in the middle of the widest part of the sea. Matthew further informs us that the wind was contrary and that Jesus came between 3 and 6 a.m. (the 4\sup th\sup* watch). They had been on the water at least nine hours and most probably rowing most of that time (they were in a fishing boat, not a little rowboat). They were tired! From the parallel accounts it is clear that Jesus sent them on their way. He deliberately sent them into a difficult and trying situation. We need to understand that He may do the same with us.\f* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w see|strong="G2334"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w walking|strong="G4043"\w* \w on|strong="G1909"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w sea|strong="G2281"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w coming|strong="G1096"\w* \w near|strong="G1451"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w boat|strong="G4143"\w*; \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w were|strong="G3588"\w* \w afraid|strong="G5399"\w*.
\v 20 \w But|strong="G1161"\w* \w He|strong="G1161"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w It|strong="G1161"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w*; don'\w t|strong="G3588"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* \w afraid|strong="G5399"\w*!”\f + \fr 6:20 \ft Only Matthew records that Peter also took a little walk.\f*
\v 21 \w Then|strong="G3767"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w wanted|strong="G2309"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w receive|strong="G2983"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w boat|strong="G4143"\w*,\f + \fr 6:21 \ft They were ready for some help.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w immediately|strong="G2112"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w boat|strong="G4143"\w* \w was|strong="G1096"\w* \w at|strong="G1909"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w land|strong="G1093"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w which|strong="G3739"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w were|strong="G3588"\w* \w going|strong="G5217"\w*.\f + \fr 6:21 \ft They were still some four miles from Bethsaida, so here we have another remarkable miracle—Jesus transported the boat those four miles instantaneously. There have been repeated references to crossing the sea, so the reading of the so-called ‘critical text’ in Luke 9:10 that places the feeding of the 5,000 in the town of Bethsaida is patently ridiculous. What would motivate the editors to print such a ridiculous reading in their text?\f*
\p 
\v 22 \w The|strong="G2532"\w* \w next|strong="G1887"\w* \w day|strong="G1887"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w crowd|strong="G3793"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w had|strong="G2424"\w* \w stayed|strong="G1510"\w* \w on|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w other|strong="G4008"\w* \w side|strong="G4008"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w sea|strong="G2281"\w*,\f + \fr 6:22 \ft These were men who stayed on the scene; I assume that they bedded down on the grass right there, waiting for Jesus to come down from the mountain—these were decision makers, and they still wanted to make Jesus king.\f* \w having|strong="G2532"\w* \w seen|strong="G3708"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w there|strong="G1563"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w no|strong="G3756"\w* \w other|strong="G4008"\w* \w boat|strong="G4143"\w* \w there|strong="G1563"\w* \w except|strong="G1487"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w one|strong="G1520"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w which|strong="G3588"\w* \w His|strong="G1519"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w* \w had|strong="G2424"\w* \w entered|strong="G4897"\w*,\f + \fr 6:22 \ft Around 4% of the Greek manuscripts, of inferior quality, omit “except the one into which His disciples had entered” (as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.).\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w had|strong="G2424"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* gotten \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w boat|strong="G4143"\w* \w with|strong="G2532"\w* \w His|strong="G1519"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w* \w but|strong="G2532"\w* \w only|strong="G3441"\w* \w His|strong="G1519"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w* \w had|strong="G2424"\w* gone away—
\v 23 although \w other|strong="G3588"\w* \w boats|strong="G4142"\w* \w had|strong="G3588"\w* \w come|strong="G2064"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w Tiberias|strong="G5085"\w*,\f + \fr 6:23 \ft The point seems to be that only one boat came with Jesus, so when it left there was no other at His disposal. The boats from Tiberias doubtless returned home for the night (the town was not far and the owners would prefer to sleep in their beds).\f* \w near|strong="G1451"\w* \w the|strong="G1537"\w* \w place|strong="G5117"\w* \w where|strong="G3699"\w* \w they|strong="G3588"\w* \w ate|strong="G2068"\w* \w the|strong="G1537"\w* bread \w after|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G1537"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w* \w had|strong="G3588"\w* \w given|strong="G2168"\w* \w thanks|strong="G2168"\w*—
\v 24 \w so|strong="G3767"\w* \w when|strong="G3753"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w crowd|strong="G3793"\w* \w saw|strong="G3708"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w neither|strong="G3761"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w nor|strong="G3761"\w* \w His|strong="G1519"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w* \w were|strong="G1510"\w* \w there|strong="G1563"\w*, \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w got|strong="G1684"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w boats|strong="G4142"\w*\f + \fr 6:24 \ft How many people could those boats carry? Probably less than a hundred, all told, but these were special people who had stayed on the scene for a reason.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w went|strong="G2064"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w Capernaum|strong="G2584"\w*, \w looking|strong="G2212"\w* \w for|strong="G3754"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w*.\f + \fr 6:24 \ft From Matthew and Mark I gather that from Bethsaida Jesus went directly to Genesaret; verse 59 below makes clear that the men found Him in Capernaum, which was close by. So why did Jesus send the disciples to Bethsaida? Perhaps it was to give an accounting to the owner of the place where the multitude was fed—15,000 people can make quite a mess. (I suspect that Jesus had permission to use the place when He wanted to get away, but no one had foreseen such a crowd as that.)\f*
\v 25 \w When|strong="G2532"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w found|strong="G2147"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w on|strong="G1096"\w* \w another|strong="G3588"\w* \w side|strong="G4008"\w*\f + \fr 6:25 \ft There is no definite article with ‘other side’, since it was just across the bay, not the other side of the lake.\f* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w sea|strong="G2281"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Rabbi|strong="G4461"\w*, \w when|strong="G2532"\w*\f + \fr 6:25 \ft “When”, not “how”. Surely, they knew that Jesus could have taken a back trail through the hills and made it on foot without difficulty.\f* \w did|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G3004"\w* \w get|strong="G1096"\w* \w here|strong="G5602"\w*?”
\s1 The Bread of Life
\p 
\v 26 \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w*: “\w Most|strong="G1537"\w* assuredly \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w seeking|strong="G2212"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w saw|strong="G3708"\w* miraculous \w signs|strong="G4592"\w*, \w but|strong="G2532"\w* \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w ate|strong="G2068"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* bread \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w were|strong="G3588"\w* \w filled|strong="G5526"\w*.\f + \fr 6:26 \ft He does not answer their question but goes to the heart of their problem—they want to make Him king for purely materialistic reasons. Certain kinds of people like free food; or maybe most people do; or maybe almost everybody does.\f*
\v 27 \w Do|strong="G3361"\w* \w not|strong="G3361"\w* \w work|strong="G2038"\w* \w for|strong="G1063"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w food|strong="G1035"\w* \w that|strong="G3739"\w* wastes away \w but|strong="G3361"\w* \w for|strong="G1063"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w food|strong="G1035"\w* \w that|strong="G3739"\w* \w endures|strong="G3306"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w life|strong="G2222"\w* eternal, \w which|strong="G3739"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w Man|strong="G3778"\w* \w will|strong="G2316"\w* \w give|strong="G1325"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w*;\f + \fr 6:27 \ft Jesus will give the Life, but they have to work for the food that endures into that Life. So how do we “work for the food”? Most people have to work so as to have food to maintain their physical health and strength, and there are clear biblical strictures against laziness, so our Lord's statement presumably has to do with priorities. ‘Making a living’ should not be our top priority; like Jesus, our top priority should be to do the Father's will (Hebrews 10:7, John 4:34). What we build in ‘gold, silver, precious stones’ (1 Corinthians 3:12) will indeed “endure into” life eternal.\f* \w because|strong="G1063"\w* \w on|strong="G1519"\w* \nd \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*\nd* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* \w has|strong="G2316"\w* \w set|strong="G4972"\w* \w His|strong="G1519"\w* \w seal|strong="G4972"\w*.”
\v 28 \w So|strong="G2443"\w* \w they|strong="G3588"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w What|strong="G5101"\w* \w should|strong="G2316"\w* \w we|strong="G2443"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w* \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w we|strong="G2443"\w* \w may|strong="G2443"\w* \w work|strong="G2041"\w* \w the|strong="G4314"\w* \w works|strong="G2041"\w* \w of|strong="G2316"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*?”\f + \fr 6:28 \ft I do not think they listened very well; they answered according to their own ideas.\f*
\v 29 \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w This|strong="G3778"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w work|strong="G2041"\w* \w of|strong="G2316"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*, \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w you|strong="G3739"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w One|strong="G3739"\w* \w whom|strong="G3739"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w sent|strong="G2316"\w*.”\f + \fr 6:29 \ft If we want to serve or please God, the first step is to believe into Jesus. After we belong to Jesus we have the privilege of participating in God's works.\f*
\v 30 \w So|strong="G2443"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w Him|strong="G3708"\w*: “\w Well|strong="G2532"\w* \w then|strong="G3767"\w*, \w what|strong="G5101"\w* \w sign|strong="G4592"\w* \w are|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w going|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w* \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w we|strong="G2532"\w* \w may|strong="G2532"\w* \w see|strong="G3708"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w*?\f + \fr 6:30 \ft These guys are hard to believe—they had seen Jesus multiply the bread and fish; how much more of a sign did they want? They had been so impressed that they wanted to make Him king. But instead of offering free food Jesus is now demanding commitment; so they start to backpedal.\f* \w What|strong="G5101"\w* \w are|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w going|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w perform|strong="G4160"\w*?
\v 31 \w Our|strong="G1722"\w* \w fathers|strong="G3962"\w* \w ate|strong="G2068"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w manna|strong="G3131"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w desert|strong="G2048"\w*, \w just|strong="G2531"\w* \w as|strong="G2531"\w* \w it|strong="G2531"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w written|strong="G1125"\w*: ‘\w He|strong="G3588"\w* \w gave|strong="G1325"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w* bread \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w Heaven|strong="G3772"\w* \w to|strong="G1722"\w* \w eat|strong="G2068"\w*.’ ”\f + \fr 6:31 \ft See Exodus 16:4, Nehemiah 9:15 and Psalm 78:24.\f*
\p 
\v 32 \w Then|strong="G3767"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w Most|strong="G1537"\w* assuredly \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, \w Moses|strong="G3475"\w* \w did|strong="G1325"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w give|strong="G1325"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w the|strong="G1537"\w* bread \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w Heaven|strong="G3772"\w*, \w but|strong="G3767"\w* \w my|strong="G1325"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* \w gives|strong="G1325"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w the|strong="G1537"\w* \nd \w true|strong="G3588"\w*\nd* bread \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w Heaven|strong="G3772"\w*.
\v 33 \w For|strong="G1063"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* bread \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w One|strong="G3588"\w* \w coming|strong="G2597"\w* \w down|strong="G2597"\w* \w out|strong="G1537"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w Heaven|strong="G3772"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w giving|strong="G1325"\w* \w Life|strong="G2222"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w world|strong="G2889"\w*.”\f + \fr 6:33 \ft Jesus said that ‘bread’ ‘gives life’. Bread was their staff of life; their physical life depended on it. Similarly, our spiritual life depends on Jesus.\f*
\v 34 \w Then|strong="G3767"\w* \w they|strong="G3588"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Lord|strong="G2962"\w*, \w give|strong="G1325"\w* \w us|strong="G1325"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* bread \w always|strong="G3842"\w*.”\f + \fr 6:34 \ft This seems to be a bit of a change in attitude. They are vacillating.\f*
\v 35 \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* bread \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Life|strong="G2222"\w*. \w Whoever|strong="G3588"\w* \w comes|strong="G2064"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* \nd \w never|strong="G3756"\w*\nd* \w hunger|strong="G3983"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w whoever|strong="G3588"\w* \w believes|strong="G4100"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* \nd \w never|strong="G3756"\w*\nd* \w thirst|strong="G1372"\w*.\f + \fr 6:35 \ft I have underlined ‘never’ because Jesus was very emphatic.\f*
\v 36 \w But|strong="G2532"\w*, \w as|strong="G2532"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w told|strong="G3004"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w actually|strong="G2532"\w* \w seen|strong="G3708"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*, \w yet|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w do|strong="G4100"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w*.
\v 37 \w All|strong="G3956"\w* \w that|strong="G3739"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* \w gives|strong="G1325"\w* \w me|strong="G1325"\w* \w will|strong="G2532"\w* \w come|strong="G2064"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w me|strong="G1325"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w one|strong="G3739"\w* \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w comes|strong="G2064"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w me|strong="G1325"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w will|strong="G2532"\w* \nd \w not|strong="G3756"\w*\nd* \w throw|strong="G1544"\w* \w out|strong="G1544"\w*;\f + \fr 6:37 \ft “All that” is in the neuter gender and presumably includes more than people; but does it \nd exclude\nd* people? “The one who” refers only to people. Jesus will not throw you out, but you can back out, decide to turn back.\f*
\v 38 \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w it|strong="G3754"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w* \w my|strong="G1699"\w* \w own|strong="G1699"\w* \w will|strong="G2307"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w have|strong="G1473"\w* \w come|strong="G2597"\w* \w down|strong="G2597"\w* \w out|strong="G2597"\w* \w of|strong="G2307"\w* \w Heaven|strong="G3772"\w*,\f + \fr 6:38 \ft Here we have a plain statement: “I have come down out of Heaven”. We can either accept it or reject it; those who say that Jesus was merely a good man are rejecting it.\f* \w but|strong="G3588"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w will|strong="G2307"\w* \w of|strong="G2307"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w One|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w sent|strong="G3992"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*.
\v 39 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w will|strong="G2307"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* Father \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w sent|strong="G3992"\w* \w me|strong="G1325"\w*, \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w should|strong="G3588"\w* lose \w nothing|strong="G3361"\w* \w out|strong="G1537"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w He|strong="G1161"\w* \w has|strong="G3739"\w* \w given|strong="G1325"\w* \w me|strong="G1325"\w*, \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w should|strong="G3588"\w* raise \w it|strong="G1161"\w*\f + \fr 6:39 \ft The manuscript evidence is badly divided here, but I take it that the best line of transmission has “it” rather than “him” (neuter rather than masculine)—in the preceding clause, “nothing out of all” is definitely neuter. The ‘problem’ is the verb “raise”—if it is taken as raising the dead then the direct object should be masculine. But “raise” is much more general in use, being used for erecting a building, lifting something up, etc. There is a contrast between verse 39 (things) and verse 40 (people). Verse 39 joins other passages that indicate that during the Millennium the earth will be restored to conditions reminiscent of Eden (compare Romans 8:19-22).\f* \w up|strong="G1325"\w* \w at|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w last|strong="G2078"\w* \w day|strong="G2250"\w*.
\v 40 \w Again|strong="G1519"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w will|strong="G2307"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w sent|strong="G2532"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*, \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w everyone|strong="G3956"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* ‘\w sees|strong="G2334"\w*’ \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w believes|strong="G4100"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w may|strong="G2532"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* eternal \w life|strong="G2222"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \bd \nd \w I|strong="G1473"\w*\nd*\bd* \w will|strong="G2307"\w* \w raise|strong="G2532"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w up|strong="G1519"\w* \w at|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w last|strong="G2078"\w* \w day|strong="G2250"\w*.”\f + \fr 6:40 \ft Since only His contemporaries could see Jesus physically, everyone else has to ‘see’ Him spiritually. But in verse 36 the Lord says that even though they were seeing Him physically, they were not believing—so even for the contemporaries the ‘seeing’ had to be spiritual. Jesus Himself will raise up His followers.\f*
\p 
\v 41 \w Then|strong="G3767"\w* \w the|strong="G1537"\w* \w Jews|strong="G2453"\w*\f + \fr 6:41 \ft I take it that up to verse 40 Jesus has been interacting with the ‘king-makers’. The “Jews” here probably represent the ruling hierarchy—since Jesus was in the synagogue there were others present besides the ‘king-makers’.\f* started complaining \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w He|strong="G3754"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w*, “\w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G1537"\w* bread \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w came|strong="G2597"\w* \w down|strong="G2597"\w* \w out|strong="G1537"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w Heaven|strong="G3772"\w*.”
\v 42 \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w were|strong="G1510"\w* \w saying|strong="G3004"\w*: “Isn'\w t|strong="G3588"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w son|strong="G5207"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w Joseph|strong="G2501"\w*, \w whose|strong="G3739"\w* \w father|strong="G3962"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w mother|strong="G3384"\w* \w we|strong="G2249"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w*?\f + \fr 6:42 \ft I wonder why they refer to \nd Joseph's\nd* parents. Of course they were assuming that Jesus was in fact Joseph's son.\f* \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w how|strong="G4459"\w* \w can|strong="G3004"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w*, ‘\w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w come|strong="G2597"\w* \w down|strong="G2597"\w* \w out|strong="G1537"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \nd \w Heaven|strong="G3772"\w*\nd*’?”\f + \fr 6:42 \ft Notice that they understood clearly that Jesus was claiming that He had come down out of Heaven.\f*
\p 
\v 43 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w them|strong="G3004"\w*: “\w Stop|strong="G3361"\w* complaining \w among|strong="G3326"\w* yourselves.
\v 44 \w No|strong="G3762"\w* \w one|strong="G3762"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w able|strong="G1410"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w come|strong="G2064"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w unless|strong="G1437"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w sent|strong="G3992"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w draws|strong="G1670"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*,\f + \fr 6:44 \ft As Jesus pointed out to Nicodemus (see note at John 3:6), without God's direct participation, no one is saved. But see the next verse.\f* \w and|strong="G2064"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w will|strong="G1473"\w* raise \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w up|strong="G3361"\w* \w at|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w last|strong="G2078"\w* \w day|strong="G2250"\w*.
\v 45 \w It|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w written|strong="G1125"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w prophets|strong="G4396"\w*, ‘\w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w will|strong="G2316"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* \w taught|strong="G1318"\w* \w by|strong="G1722"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*.’\f + \fr 6:45 \ft See Isaiah 54:13.\f* \w Therefore|strong="G3844"\w* \w everyone|strong="G3956"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* listens \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w learns|strong="G3129"\w* \w from|strong="G3844"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* \w comes|strong="G2064"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*.\f + \fr 6:45 \ft In verse 44 Jesus emphasizes God's sovereignty; here He emphasizes human responsibility. We can ‘listen and learn’, and then ‘come’. But in what sense is everyone “taught by God”? Everyone has the light of creation and is born with a conscience, at least. Perhaps there are other ways that God ‘teaches’.\f*
\v 46 (\w Not|strong="G3756"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w anyone|strong="G5100"\w* \w has|strong="G2316"\w* \w seen|strong="G3708"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w*, \w except|strong="G1487"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w One|strong="G5100"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w from|strong="G3844"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*—\nd \w He|strong="G3754"\w*\nd* \w has|strong="G2316"\w* \w seen|strong="G3708"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w*.)
\v 47 Most assuredly \w I|strong="G3004"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*: \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w one|strong="G3588"\w* \w believing|strong="G4100"\w* into \w me|strong="G3004"\w*\f + \fr 6:47 \ft About 0.5% of the Greek manuscripts, of objectively inferior quality, omit “into me” (as in NIV, NASB, TEV, etc.). But the object of one's belief is of the essence; it is impossible to live without believing in something, so everyone believes. The reading of the so-called ‘critical text’ opens the door to universalism—the more so since the Lord is making a formal statement about how to be saved.\f* \w has|strong="G2192"\w* eternal \w life|strong="G2222"\w*.
\p 
\v 48 “\w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* bread \w of|strong="G3588"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w Life|strong="G2222"\w*.\f + \fr 6:48 \ft Since the Lord is obviously not claiming to be a loaf of literal bread, this is a figure of speech, a metaphor. Bread was their staff of life; they could not live without it. Jesus is our spiritual ‘staff of life’; we cannot live spiritually without Him.\f*
\v 49 \w Your|strong="G2532"\w* \w fathers|strong="G3962"\w* \w ate|strong="G2068"\w* \w manna|strong="G3131"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w desert|strong="G2048"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w died|strong="G3588"\w*.\f + \fr 6:49 \ft I take it that this statement is in response to theirs in verse 31 above.\f*
\v 50 \w This|strong="G3778"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* bread \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w comes|strong="G2597"\w* \w down|strong="G2597"\w* \w out|strong="G1537"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w Heaven|strong="G3772"\w*, \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w anyone|strong="G5100"\w* \w may|strong="G2532"\w* \w eat|strong="G2068"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3361"\w* die.\f + \fr 6:50 \ft Verse 49 presumably refers to physical death, while verse 50 refers to spiritual death. Notice the “anyone may eat”; this is an open invitation.\f*
\v 51 \bd \nd \w I|strong="G1473"\w*\nd*\bd* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w living|strong="G2198"\w* bread \w which|strong="G3739"\w* \w came|strong="G2597"\w* \w down|strong="G2597"\w* \w out|strong="G1537"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w Heaven|strong="G3772"\w*. \w If|strong="G1437"\w* \w anyone|strong="G5100"\w* \w eats|strong="G2068"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w this|strong="G3588"\w* bread \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* \w live|strong="G2198"\w* \w forever|strong="G1519"\w*. \w Actually|strong="G2532"\w*, \w the|strong="G2532"\w* bread \w that|strong="G3739"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* \w give|strong="G1325"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w my|strong="G1325"\w* \w flesh|strong="G4561"\w*,\f + \fr 6:51 \ft I take it that He is referring to His physical body, which represents the incarnation, with all that involved.\f* \w which|strong="G3739"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* \w give|strong="G1325"\w* \w on|strong="G1519"\w* \w behalf|strong="G5228"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w life|strong="G2222"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w world|strong="G2889"\w*.”\f + \fr 6:51 \ft “The life of the world”—wow! Well, according to Romans 8:19-23 the whole creation is groaning, waiting for redemption.\f*
\s2 Chew flesh, drink blood
\p 
\v 52 \w At|strong="G4314"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w the|strong="G4314"\w* \w Jews|strong="G2453"\w* started quarrelling \w among|strong="G4314"\w* \w themselves|strong="G3778"\w*, \w saying|strong="G3004"\w*, “\w How|strong="G4459"\w* \w can|strong="G1410"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w man|strong="G3778"\w* \w give|strong="G1325"\w* \w us|strong="G1325"\w* \w his|strong="G1325"\w* \w flesh|strong="G4561"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w eat|strong="G2068"\w*?!”\f + \fr 6:52 \ft They were being strictly literal, which could not be right—if they had started cutting Him up right there, they would have killed Him, and only those physically present could have eaten and drunk.\f*
\v 53 \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*: “Most assuredly \w I|strong="G2532"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, \w unless|strong="G1437"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w eat|strong="G2068"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w flesh|strong="G4561"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Man|strong="G3361"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w drink|strong="G4095"\w* \w His|strong="G1438"\w* blood, \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w do|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w Life|strong="G2222"\w* \w within|strong="G1722"\w* \w yourselves|strong="G1438"\w*.
\v 54 \w Whoever|strong="G3588"\w* chews\f + \fr 6:54 \ft The verb here is different from the “eat” in verse 53. The verb here would typically be used of a cow munching fodder, but fodder is usually crunchy, so the munching is noisy. Because “munch” suggests noise, I have rendered “chew”. In verse 56 chewing is linked to abiding, something we need to do every day.\f* \w my|strong="G5176"\w* \w flesh|strong="G4561"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w drinks|strong="G4095"\w* \w my|strong="G5176"\w* blood \w has|strong="G2192"\w* eternal \w life|strong="G2222"\w*,\f + \fr 6:54 \ft The Roman Church takes this literally when they claim that during their Mass the priest actually converts the elements into flesh and blood (transubstantiation). But since John repeatedly records that it is by believing into Jesus, or His name, that one receives eternal life, then we should understand the eating and drinking here as metaphoric.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w will|strong="G2532"\w* \w raise|strong="G2532"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w up|strong="G2532"\w* \w at|strong="G2250"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w last|strong="G2078"\w* \w day|strong="G2250"\w*.
