\p 
\v 50 \w Nicodemus|strong="G3530"\w* (\w the|strong="G1537"\w* \w one|strong="G1520"\w* \w who|strong="G1520"\w* \w came|strong="G2064"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w Him|strong="G1438"\w* \w at|strong="G4314"\w* night, \w being|strong="G1510"\w* \w one|strong="G1520"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w them|strong="G1438"\w*) \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w them|strong="G1438"\w*,
\v 51 “\w Our|strong="G2532"\w* \w law|strong="G3551"\w* doesn'\w t|strong="G3588"\w* \w judge|strong="G2919"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w man|strong="G3361"\w* \w before|strong="G3844"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* hears \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w knows|strong="G1097"\w* \w what|strong="G5101"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w doing|strong="G4160"\w*, \w does|strong="G4160"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w*?”
\v 52 \w They|strong="G2532"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w You|strong="G4771"\w* aren'\w t|strong="G3588"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w Galilee|strong="G1056"\w* \w too|strong="G2532"\w*, \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w*? \w Search|strong="G2045"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w see|strong="G3708"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w no|strong="G3756"\w* \w prophet|strong="G4396"\w* \w has|strong="G3708"\w* \w ever|strong="G3756"\w* \w arisen|strong="G1453"\w* \w out|strong="G1537"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w Galilee|strong="G1056"\w*.”\f + \fr 7:52 \ft A bit of an overstatement—Jonah was from Gath Hepher of Zebulun, north of Natsareth (2 Kings 14:25).\f*
\v 53 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w each|strong="G1538"\w* \w one|strong="G1538"\w* \w went|strong="G4198"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w his|strong="G1519"\w* own \w house|strong="G3624"\w*.\f + \fr 7:53 \ft Some 15% of the Greek manuscripts omit 7:53-8:11, including most of the early ones; but that means that 85% contain it, including the Latin tradition that dates from the 2\sup nd\sup* century. Assuming (for the sake of the argument) that the passage is spurious, how could it ever have intruded here, and to such effect that it is attested by some 85% of the MSS? Let's try to read the larger passage without these verses—we must go from 7:52 to 8:12 directly. Reviewing the context, the chief priests and Pharisees had sent officers to arrest Jesus, to no avail; a ‘discussion’ ensues; Nicodemus makes a point, to which the Pharisees answer:\fp (7:52) “Are you also from Galilee? Search and look, for no prophet has arisen out of Galilee.”\fp (8:12) Then Jesus spoke to them again, saying, “I am the light of the world…”\fp What is the antecedent of “them”, and what is the meaning of “again”? By the normal rules of grammar, if 7:53—8:11 is missing then “them” must refer to the “Pharisees” and “again” means that there has already been at least one prior exchange. But, 7:45 makes clear that Jesus \bd was not there\bd* with the Pharisees. Thus, UBS [the ‘critical’ text] introduces an aberration. And yet, Metzger claims that the passage “interrupts the sequence of 7.52 and 8.12 ff.” (p. 220)! To look for the antecedents of 8:12 in 7:37-39 not only does despite to the syntax but also runs afoul of 8:13—“the Pharisees” respond to Jesus' claim in verse 12, but “the Pharisees” are somewhere else, 7:45-52 (if the Pericope is absent).\fp Metzger also claims that “the style and vocabulary of the pericope differ noticeably from the rest of the Fourth Gospel”—but, would not the native speakers of Greek at that time have been in a better position than modern critics to notice something like that? So how could they allow such an “extraneous” passage to be forced into the text? I submit that the evident answer is that they did not; it was there all the time. I also protest their use of brackets here. Since the editors clearly regard the passage to be spurious they should be consistent and delete it, as do NEB and Williams. That way the full extent of their error would be open for all to see. Unfortunately, NIV, NASB, NRSV, Berkeley and TEV also use brackets to question the legitimacy of this passage.\fp But why was the story omitted? Leading church father and theologian, Augustine (about \sc ad\sc* 430), answers: “Certain persons of little faith, or rather enemies of the true faith, fearing, I suppose, lest their wives should be given impunity in sinning, removed from their manuscripts the Lord's acts of forgiveness toward the adulteress, as if He who said ‘sin no more’ had granted permission to sin.” (See Augustine, “Adulterous Marriages” [2.7] trans. by Charles T. Huegelmeyer, in \it Saint Augustine: Treatises on Marriage and Other Subjects\it* [New York: Fathers of the Church, 1955], p. 107.) [I took this material on Augustine from \it Living Water: The Gospel of John—Logos 21 Version\it*, Absolutely Free Incorporated, p. 74.]\f*
\c 8
\s1 The Light of the world at work
\m 
\v 1 \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w went|strong="G4198"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w Mount|strong="G3735"\w* \w of|strong="G2424"\w* \w Olives|strong="G1636"\w*.\f + \fr 8:1 \ft There is a basic three-way split in the manuscript attestation for these twelve verses (7:53-8:11)—the three major groups represent three lines of transmission that are both ancient and independent. It follows that where two agree against one, the two presumably retain the original reading. In these verses there are 25 places where two groups agree against one, six others where 2½ agree against ½, and just one place where each of the three major groups has its own reading. It happens that one of the three groups is always in the majority (in the 31 places), so it is the only one that is always right in those 31 places—so in the one place where there is a three-way split I follow that group, because it has the best credibility quotient.\f*
\v 2 \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w at|strong="G1519"\w* \w dawn|strong="G3722"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w went|strong="G2064"\w* \w again|strong="G3825"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w temple|strong="G2411"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w people|strong="G2992"\w* \w were|strong="G3588"\w* \w coming|strong="G2064"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*; \w so|strong="G2532"\w* \w sitting|strong="G2523"\w* \w down|strong="G2523"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* started \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w teach|strong="G1321"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*.
\s2 A dirty deal
\p 
\v 3 \w Then|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w scribes|strong="G1122"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Pharisees|strong="G5330"\w* \w bring|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w woman|strong="G1135"\w* \w caught|strong="G2638"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w adultery|strong="G3430"\w*; \w and|strong="G2532"\w* placing \w her|strong="G3588"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w center|strong="G3319"\w*
\v 4 \w they|strong="G3588"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w Teacher|strong="G1320"\w*, \w we|strong="G3778"\w* \w found|strong="G2638"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w woman|strong="G1135"\w* \w committing|strong="G3431"\w* \w adultery|strong="G3431"\w*, \w in|strong="G3004"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w very|strong="G3778"\w* \w act|strong="G1888"\w*.
\v 5 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w our|strong="G1722"\w* \w law|strong="G3551"\w* \w Moses|strong="G3475"\w* \w commanded|strong="G1781"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w such|strong="G5108"\w* \w women|strong="G5108"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w be|strong="G3588"\w* \w stoned|strong="G3036"\w*;\f + \fr 8:5 \ft According to Leviticus 20:10 \bd both\bd* the man and the woman were to be executed—so where is the man? This was obviously a put-up job; if they got her “in the act” the man was probably one of them. Those guys were dirty!\f* \w so|strong="G3767"\w* \w what|strong="G5101"\w* \w do|strong="G5101"\w* \nd \w you|strong="G4771"\w*\nd* \w say|strong="G3004"\w*?”
\v 6 \w They|strong="G1161"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w test|strong="G3985"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w they|strong="G1161"\w* \w might|strong="G3778"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w an|strong="G2192"\w* \w accusation|strong="G2723"\w* \w against|strong="G1519"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*.
\p \w But|strong="G1161"\w* stooping \w down|strong="G2736"\w*\f + \fr 8:6 \ft Recall that He is sitting, so He just bends forward so as to reach the ground.\f* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w began|strong="G2192"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w write|strong="G1125"\w* \w on|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w ground|strong="G1093"\w* \w with|strong="G1519"\w* \w His|strong="G1519"\w* \w finger|strong="G1147"\w*, taking \w no|strong="G3588"\w* notice.
\v 7 \w But|strong="G1161"\w* \w since|strong="G5613"\w* \w they|strong="G1161"\w* kept \w on|strong="G1909"\w* \w asking|strong="G2065"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, straightening \w up|strong="G1909"\w* \w He|strong="G1161"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Let|strong="G1161"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w one|strong="G3588"\w* \w without|strong="G5613"\w* sin \w among|strong="G4314"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* throw \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w first|strong="G4413"\w* \w stone|strong="G3037"\w* \w at|strong="G1909"\w* \w her|strong="G3588"\w*.”
\v 8 \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w stooping|strong="G2532"\w* \w down|strong="G2736"\w* \w again|strong="G3825"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* continued \w writing|strong="G1125"\w* \w on|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w ground|strong="G1093"\w*.\f + \fr 8:8 \ft A small minority of the manuscripts completes the verse with “the sins of each one of them”. I, for one, would like to know what Jesus wrote, and I wouldn't be surprised if He wrote just that, but I take it that John did not record that phrase.\f*
\v 9 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w upon|strong="G1722"\w* hearing \it this\it*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w being|strong="G2532"\w* \w convicted|strong="G1651"\w* \w by|strong="G1722"\w* \w their|strong="G2532"\w* \w conscience|strong="G4893"\w*, \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w began|strong="G1161"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w go|strong="G1831"\w* \w out|strong="G1831"\w* \w one|strong="G1520"\w* \w by|strong="G1722"\w* \w one|strong="G1520"\w*, starting \w with|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w older|strong="G4245"\w* \w ones|strong="G4245"\w* \w down|strong="G2596"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* least. \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w only|strong="G3441"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* \w left|strong="G2641"\w*, \w with|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w woman|strong="G1135"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w center|strong="G3319"\w*.\f + \fr 8:9 \ft The center of what? The center of the crowd—the accusers had all left, but the crowd wasn't going any place! They hadn't seen a show like this for a long time!\f*
\p 
\v 10 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* straightening \w up|strong="G2532"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3367"\w* \w seeing|strong="G2300"\w* \w anyone|strong="G3367"\w* \w except|strong="G4133"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w woman|strong="G1135"\w*, \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w her|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w Where|strong="G4226"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w accusers|strong="G2725"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w yours|strong="G4771"\w*? \w Has|strong="G3762"\w* \w no|strong="G3762"\w* \w one|strong="G3762"\w* \w condemned|strong="G2632"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w*?”
\v 11 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w she|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w*, “\w No|strong="G3762"\w* \w one|strong="G3762"\w*, \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w*.” \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w her|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w Neither|strong="G3761"\w* \w do|strong="G2532"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w condemn|strong="G2632"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w*.\f + \fr 8:11 \ft Jesus was not even a witness, and it required at least two witnesses to condemn; so of course He could not condemn her. But He makes clear that He does not condone her behavior.\f* \w Go|strong="G4198"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w from|strong="G2532"\w* \w now|strong="G1161"\w* \w on|strong="G4198"\w* don'\w t|strong="G3588"\w* sin \w any|strong="G3762"\w* \w more|strong="G3371"\w*!”
\s2 Jesus dialogs with the Pharisees
\p 
\v 12 \w Then|strong="G3767"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w spoke|strong="G2980"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w* \w again|strong="G3825"\w*,\f + \fr 8:12 \ft “Them” refers to the crowd, and “again” means that He resumes His teaching after having been so rudely interrupted. The interruption occupies verses 3-11, so we are referred back to verse 2.\f* \w saying|strong="G3004"\w*: “\w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Light|strong="G5457"\w* \w of|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w world|strong="G2889"\w*. \w Whoever|strong="G3588"\w* \w follows|strong="G3004"\w* \nd \w me|strong="G1473"\w*\nd* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* \nd \w not|strong="G3756"\w*\nd* \w walk|strong="G4043"\w* \w around|strong="G4043"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w darkness|strong="G4653"\w*,\f + \fr 8:12 \ft “The darkness” = Satan's kingdom.\f* \w but|strong="G3361"\w* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w light|strong="G5457"\w* \w of|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Life|strong="G2222"\w*.”\f + \fr 8:12 \ft There is a certain secret society that requires a candidate to declare that he is coming out of darkness in search of light. A Christian who does this is formally denying Jesus.\f*
\v 13 \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w Pharisees|strong="G5330"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w You|strong="G4771"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w testifying|strong="G3140"\w* \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w yourself|strong="G4572"\w*; \w your|strong="G3588"\w* \w testimony|strong="G3141"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* valid.”
\v 14 \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w Even|strong="G2532"\w* \w though|strong="G2532"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w testify|strong="G3140"\w* \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w myself|strong="G1683"\w*, \w my|strong="G1473"\w* \w testimony|strong="G3141"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* valid, \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w where|strong="G4226"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w came|strong="G2064"\w* \w from|strong="G2064"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w where|strong="G4226"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* \w going|strong="G5217"\w*.\f + \fr 8:14 \ft An interesting argument—why would His knowing His origin and destination validate His witness? I imagine that He is really referring to His identity; as God His witness is always valid.\f* \w But|strong="G1161"\w* \nd \w you|strong="G5210"\w*\nd* \w do|strong="G1492"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w where|strong="G4226"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w come|strong="G2064"\w* \w from|strong="G2064"\w* \w or|strong="G2228"\w* \w where|strong="G4226"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* \w going|strong="G5217"\w*.
\v 15 \nd \w You|strong="G5210"\w*\nd* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w judging|strong="G2919"\w* \w according|strong="G2596"\w* \w to|strong="G2596"\w* \w the|strong="G2596"\w* \w flesh|strong="G4561"\w*; \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1473"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w judging|strong="G2919"\w* \w anyone|strong="G3762"\w*.
\v 16 \w Yet|strong="G2532"\w* \w even|strong="G2532"\w* \w if|strong="G1437"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w do|strong="G2919"\w* \w judge|strong="G2919"\w*, \w my|strong="G1699"\w* \w judging|strong="G2919"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* valid, \w in|strong="G2532"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w alone|strong="G3441"\w* \it in judging\it*, \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w sent|strong="G3992"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \it are together\it*.
\v 17 \w It|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w written|strong="G1125"\w* precisely \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \nd \w your|strong="G5212"\w*\nd* \w law|strong="G3551"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w testimony|strong="G3141"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w two|strong="G1417"\w* \w men|strong="G1417"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* valid:
\v 18 \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* \w one|strong="G3588"\w* \w testifying|strong="G3140"\w* \w concerning|strong="G4012"\w* \w myself|strong="G1683"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w sent|strong="G3992"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w testifies|strong="G3140"\w* \w concerning|strong="G4012"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*.”
\v 19 \w Then|strong="G3767"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Where|strong="G4226"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w your|strong="G2532"\w* \w father|strong="G3962"\w*?”\f + \fr 8:19 \ft Their question is reasonable. Since Jesus is adducing His Father as a witness they want to know where they can find Him, to confirm the witness. But Jesus does not give a direct answer, as He usually did not, when dealing with Pharisees.\f* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w*: “\w You|strong="G4771"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w neither|strong="G3777"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w nor|strong="G3777"\w* \w my|strong="G1473"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w*. \w If|strong="G1487"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w knew|strong="G1492"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w would|strong="G2532"\w* \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w my|strong="G1473"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w*.”
\v 20 \w Jesus|strong="G2532"\w* \w spoke|strong="G2980"\w* \w these|strong="G3778"\w* \w words|strong="G4487"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w treasury|strong="G1049"\w*, \w while|strong="G1722"\w* \w teaching|strong="G1321"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w temple|strong="G2413"\w*; \w yet|strong="G2532"\w* \w no|strong="G3762"\w* \w one|strong="G3762"\w* arrested \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w His|strong="G1722"\w* \w time|strong="G5610"\w* \w had|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3762"\w* \w yet|strong="G2532"\w* \w come|strong="G2064"\w*.\f + \fr 8:20 \ft Supernatural intervention is implied.\f*
\s2 “you will die in your sins”
\p 
\v 21 \w Then|strong="G3767"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G3004"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w* \w again|strong="G3825"\w*: “\w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1473"\w* \w going|strong="G5217"\w* \w away|strong="G5217"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w will|strong="G2532"\w* look \w for|strong="G1722"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w will|strong="G2532"\w* die \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w your|strong="G2532"\w* sin. \w Where|strong="G3699"\w* \bd \nd \w I|strong="G1473"\w*\nd*\bd* \w am|strong="G1473"\w* \w going|strong="G5217"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w cannot|strong="G1410"\w* \w come|strong="G2064"\w*.”\f + \fr 8:21 \ft I wonder if the Lord is not referring to two future stages, short and long range. Since there are still six months to go until His death, He will go away from Jerusalem (He divided those six months between Judea and Perea) and they will be looking for Him, to kill Him. That is the short range. Long range—since they will not repent they will die lost and so not go to Heaven.\f*
\v 22 \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w Jews|strong="G2453"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w*, “\w He|strong="G3754"\w* won'\w t|strong="G3588"\w* kill \w himself|strong="G1438"\w*, \w will|strong="G1473"\w* \w he|strong="G3754"\w*, \w since|strong="G3754"\w* \w he|strong="G3754"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w*, ‘\w Where|strong="G3699"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1473"\w* \w going|strong="G5217"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w cannot|strong="G1410"\w* \w come|strong="G2064"\w*’?”\f + \fr 8:22 \ft But of course they could kill themselves too, and would die sooner or later in any case, so they would be together in Hades (on that hypothesis).\f*
\v 23 \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w You|strong="G5210"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w below|strong="G2736"\w*; \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* Above. \w You|strong="G5210"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w world|strong="G2889"\w*; \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w world|strong="G2889"\w*.\f + \fr 8:23 \ft Here we have a plain statement.\f*
\v 24 \w That|strong="G3754"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w why|strong="G1063"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w told|strong="G3004"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* die \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w your|strong="G1437"\w* sins, \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w if|strong="G1437"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w do|strong="G3004"\w* \w not|strong="G3361"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w*,\f + \fr 8:24 \ft Most versions supply a ‘He’, making the phrase “I am He”; but the Text just has “I am”. Any Jew would immediately think of Jehovah calling Himself ‘I am’. Having just said that He was from Above, and not of this world, it seems to me clear that Jesus is claiming to be Jehovah—but they just do not want to get the point.\f* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* die \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w your|strong="G1437"\w* sins.”\f + \fr 8:24 \ft To “die in your sins” is to be spiritually lost. If they do not recognize Him as the Messiah, they are lost. They have already seen more than enough evidence, but have rejected it; since Jesus knows that they are not going to turn around, He states that they are lost. (Here it is ‘sins’ (pl) while in verse 21 it is ‘sin’ (sg); if a difference is intended I don't know what it is.)\f*
\v 25 \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Who|strong="G3739"\w* \nd \w are|strong="G1510"\w*\nd* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*?” \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w Just|strong="G2532"\w* \w what|strong="G5101"\w* \w I|strong="G3739"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w been|strong="G1510"\w* \w saying|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w from|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* beginning.
\v 26 \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w many|strong="G4183"\w* \w things|strong="G3778"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w say|strong="G2980"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w judge|strong="G2919"\w* \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, \w but|strong="G2532"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w sent|strong="G3992"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w true|strong="G3588"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w what|strong="G3739"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w myself|strong="G1473"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* heard \w from|strong="G3844"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*—\w these|strong="G3778"\w* \w things|strong="G3778"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w say|strong="G2980"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w world|strong="G2889"\w*.”\f + \fr 8:26 \ft Again, Jesus links His teaching directly to the Father.\f*
\v 27 \w They|strong="G3588"\w* \w did|strong="G1097"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w understand|strong="G1097"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w He|strong="G3754"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* \w speaking|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w* \w about|strong="G3588"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w*.\f + \fr 8:27 \ft But they should have—their blind spot may have been the result of supernatural interference. (In John 5:17-18 they had already understood that He was making Himself equal with God.)\f*
\v 28 \w Then|strong="G3767"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w When|strong="G3752"\w* \w you|strong="G3752"\w* \w lift|strong="G5312"\w* \w up|strong="G5312"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Man|strong="G3778"\w*, \w then|strong="G3767"\w* \w you|strong="G3752"\w* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* \w know|strong="G1097"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w*\f + \fr 8:28 \ft With the supernatural darkness from 12:00 to 3:00, the earthquake, the torn veil, and later the report of the guards at the tomb, they would know for sure that they had crucified the Messiah. But they would not (perhaps could not) repent. Their doom was sealed.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w* \w nothing|strong="G3762"\w* \w from|strong="G2532"\w* \w myself|strong="G1683"\w*; \w but|strong="G2532"\w* \w just|strong="G2531"\w* \w as|strong="G2531"\w* \w my|strong="G1473"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* \w has|strong="G3962"\w* \w taught|strong="G1321"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*, \w these|strong="G3778"\w* \w things|strong="G3778"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w speak|strong="G2980"\w*.
\v 29 \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w One|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w sent|strong="G3992"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w with|strong="G3326"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*. \w The|strong="G2532"\w* Father \w has|strong="G3748"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* left \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w alone|strong="G3441"\w*, \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w always|strong="G3842"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w things|strong="G3588"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* please \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*.”\f + \fr 8:29 \ft Presumably if we always did the things that please the Father He would not leave us alone either. I suspect that when we choose to do wrong the Father lets us fend for ourselves.\f*
\s2 “the Truth will make you free”
\p 
\v 30 \w While|strong="G2980"\w* \w He|strong="G3778"\w* \w was|strong="G2980"\w* \w saying|strong="G2980"\w* \w these|strong="G3778"\w* \w things|strong="G3778"\w* \w many|strong="G4183"\w* \w believed|strong="G4100"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w Him|strong="G1519"\w*.
\v 31 \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w Jews|strong="G2453"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w had|strong="G2424"\w* \w believed|strong="G4100"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w If|strong="G1437"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w abide|strong="G3306"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w my|strong="G1699"\w* \w word|strong="G3056"\w*, \w you|strong="G5210"\w* really \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w my|strong="G1699"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w*;\f + \fr 8:31 \ft So what happens if we \nd don't\nd* abide in His Word? And how can you abide in something that doesn't exist (for you)? There are still thousands of languages spoken in the world that do not have even one verse of the Bible translated into them. How can speakers of such languages be true disciples of Jesus? I have actually heard some who claim they have been ‘baptized in the Spirit’ say they don't need the Bible, because the Holy Spirit speaks to them directly. Now why would the Holy Spirit speak to someone who disagrees with the Lord Jesus? In this connection, notice especially John 16:14-15.\f*
\v 32 \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w will|strong="G2532"\w* \w know|strong="G1097"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* Truth, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* Truth \w will|strong="G2532"\w* \w make|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w free|strong="G1659"\w*.”\f + \fr 8:32 \ft Free from what? Free from self, free from sin.\f*
\v 33 \w They|strong="G2532"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w Him|strong="G2532"\w*: “\w We|strong="G3754"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w descendants|strong="G4690"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* Abraham \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w never|strong="G3762"\w* \w been|strong="G1510"\w* \w enslaved|strong="G1398"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w anyone|strong="G3762"\w*. \w How|strong="G4459"\w* \w can|strong="G3004"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w*, ‘\w You|strong="G4771"\w* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* \w be|strong="G1096"\w* \w made|strong="G1096"\w* \w free|strong="G1658"\w*’?”\f + \fr 8:33 \ft The ones who were believing were sprinkled throughout the crowd, but Jesus' opponents were still in the front row. I assume from verse 37 that it is the opponents who speak here in verse 33. They conveniently forget that they are under the Roman yoke.\f*
\v 34 \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w I|strong="G3754"\w* \w tell|strong="G3004"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* most assuredly \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w everyone|strong="G3956"\w* committing sin \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w a|strong="G1510"\w* \w slave|strong="G1401"\w* \w of|strong="G1401"\w* sin.\f + \fr 8:34 \ft Apart from Jesus Christ every human being is a slave of sin. The only way out is to become a slave of Jesus Christ. The only true freedom available in this life is through submission to Him.\f*
\v 35 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w slave|strong="G1401"\w* \w does|strong="G3306"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w remain|strong="G3306"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w household|strong="G3614"\w* \w forever|strong="G1519"\w*; \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w son|strong="G5207"\w* \w does|strong="G3306"\w* \w remain|strong="G3306"\w* \w forever|strong="G1519"\w*.\f + \fr 8:35 \ft A son becomes part of the genealogical record, a slave does not. Some versions capitalize “Son” here (as in the next verse), but I take it that Jesus is making a generic statement. However, in verse 36 it must be “Son”, because “make \nd you\nd* free” is plural, referring to His hearers.\f*
\v 36 \w Therefore|strong="G3767"\w*, \w if|strong="G1437"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w should|strong="G3588"\w* \w make|strong="G3767"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w free|strong="G1658"\w*, \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w really|strong="G3689"\w* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* \w free|strong="G1658"\w*.
\v 37 \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w descendants|strong="G4690"\w* \w of|strong="G3056"\w* Abraham, \w but|strong="G3588"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* wanting \w to|strong="G2212"\w* kill \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w my|strong="G1699"\w* \w word|strong="G3056"\w* finds \w no|strong="G3756"\w* \w place|strong="G5562"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*.\f + \fr 8:37 \ft Their hearts were closed against His message. He was demanding a change of world view.\f*
\v 38 \w On|strong="G4160"\w* \w my|strong="G3708"\w* \w part|strong="G1473"\w*, \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w speak|strong="G2980"\w* \w what|strong="G3739"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* observed \w with|strong="G3844"\w* \w my|strong="G3708"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w*, \w while|strong="G2980"\w* \w on|strong="G4160"\w* \w your|strong="G2532"\w* \w part|strong="G1473"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w* \w what|strong="G3739"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* observed \w with|strong="G3844"\w* \w your|strong="G2532"\w* \w father|strong="G3962"\w*.”\f + \fr 8:38 \ft Jesus has affirmed several times that He could observe the Father, but in what sense could the Jews observe Satan? Our Lord's statement makes me curious. Perhaps the Jews were doing what they saw Satan doing (rather than seeing him physically). Some 10% of the Greek manuscripts have ‘heard from’ rather than “observed with”.\f*
\s2 “your father is the devil”
\p 
\v 39 \w They|strong="G2532"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Our|strong="G2424"\w* \w father|strong="G3962"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* Abraham!” \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w If|strong="G1487"\w* \w you|strong="G1487"\w* \w were|strong="G1510"\w* \w children|strong="G5043"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* Abraham, \w you|strong="G1487"\w* \w would|strong="G2532"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w works|strong="G2041"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* Abraham;
\v 40 \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w now|strong="G1161"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* wanting \w to|strong="G2212"\w* kill \w me|strong="G1473"\w*, \w a|strong="G4160"\w* \w man|strong="G3778"\w* \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w has|strong="G2316"\w* \w told|strong="G2980"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* truth \w which|strong="G3739"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* heard \w from|strong="G3844"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*.\f + \fr 8:40 \ft Here Jesus identifies clearly the source of His teaching: ‘my Father’ equals ‘God’.\f* \w This|strong="G3778"\w* \it sort of thing\it* Abraham \w did|strong="G4160"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w*!
\v 41 \w You|strong="G5210"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w* \w the|strong="G1537"\w* \w works|strong="G2041"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w your|strong="G2192"\w* \w father|strong="G3962"\w*.” \w Then|strong="G3004"\w* \w they|strong="G3588"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\nd \w We|strong="G2249"\w*\nd* \w were|strong="G3588"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w born|strong="G1080"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w fornication|strong="G4202"\w*;\f + \fr 8:41 \ft The Jews had doubtless done exhaustive research on Jesus. They knew that He was born within six months after the wedding of Joseph and Mary, and that He was born full size. [Recall that Jesus had been rejected by the people of Natsareth, so there were plenty of people who would be happy to ‘spill the beans’.] Assuming, as they did, that the father was human, whether Joseph himself or someone else, Jesus would be the result of fornication. So they here throw that information in Jesus' face.\f* \w we|strong="G2249"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w one|strong="G1520"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w*—\w God|strong="G2316"\w*.”\f + \fr 8:41 \ft Since Jesus has rejected their claim to Abraham, they now claim God!\f*
\v 42 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w If|strong="G1487"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w were|strong="G1510"\w* \w your|strong="G2532"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w*, \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w would|strong="G2316"\w* love \w me|strong="G1473"\w*, \w because|strong="G1063"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w came|strong="G2064"\w* \w forth|strong="G1831"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* \w here|strong="G1510"\w*.\f + \fr 8:42 \ft As John will write later, “he who does not love his brother whom he has seen, how can he love God whom he has not seen?” (1 John 4:20). So anyone who loved the Father (not having seen Him) would certainly love the Son who was physically present and visible. Jesus keeps reiterating His divine origin.\f* Further, \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3761"\w* \w come|strong="G2064"\w* \w on|strong="G1537"\w* \w my|strong="G1473"\w* \w own|strong="G1683"\w*, \w but|strong="G2532"\w* \nd \w He|strong="G2532"\w*\nd* \w sent|strong="G2316"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*.
\v 43 \w Why|strong="G5101"\w* don'\w t|strong="G3588"\w* \w you|strong="G3754"\w* \w understand|strong="G1097"\w* \w what|strong="G5101"\w* \w I|strong="G3754"\w* \w say|strong="G3056"\w*?—\w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w you|strong="G3754"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w able|strong="G1410"\w* \w to|strong="G1410"\w* \it really\it* \w hear|strong="G5101"\w* \w my|strong="G1699"\w* \w word|strong="G3056"\w*.\f + \fr 8:43 \ft Their ‘father’ had blinded their minds (2 Corinthians 4:4). Those Jewish leaders were “sons of the disobedience” if there ever were any, and Satan is actively at work in such people (Ephesians 2:2).\f*
\v 44 \w You|strong="G5210"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w your|strong="G2532"\w* \w father|strong="G3962"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w devil|strong="G1228"\w*,\f + \fr 8:44 \ft 1 John 3:8 makes clear that in fact Satan has lots of other ‘children’.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w desires|strong="G1939"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w your|strong="G2532"\w* \w father|strong="G3962"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w want|strong="G2309"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w*. \nd \w He|strong="G2532"\w*\nd* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* murderer\f + \fr 8:44 \ft They want to murder Jesus, showing thereby that they are worthy sons of their father. Satan instigated the death of the first couple, and may have influenced Cain to kill Abel.\f* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* beginning \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w has|strong="G3962"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w stood|strong="G2476"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* truth, \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w there|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w no|strong="G3756"\w* truth \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*.\f + \fr 8:44 \ft If there is no truth in Satan then I conclude that it is impossible for him to tell the whole, undistorted truth. He may tell a partial truth, etc., but always with the intent to deceive.\f* \w Whenever|strong="G3752"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w speaks|strong="G2980"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w lie|strong="G5579"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w speaks|strong="G2980"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w his|strong="G1722"\w* \w own|strong="G2398"\w* \w things|strong="G3588"\w*, \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w liar|strong="G5583"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w father|strong="G3962"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \it lying\it*.\f + \fr 8:44 \ft So whenever we tell a lie we are doing Satan's thing. And whenever we accept a lie (like evolutionism, Marxism, Freudianism, humanism, relativism, etc.) we give Satan a foothold in our minds, which he usually turns into a stronghold.\f*
\v 45 \w But|strong="G1161"\w* \w since|strong="G3754"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w speak|strong="G3004"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* truth \w you|strong="G3754"\w* \w do|strong="G3004"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*.
\v 46 \w Which|strong="G5101"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w convicts|strong="G1651"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* sin?\f + \fr 8:46 \ft I suppose that the point here is that if they could point to any sin in His life this would raise a question about His character, and therefore about His credibility. But since they can't, His character is above question; so they should believe Him.\f* \w So|strong="G1223"\w* \w if|strong="G1487"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w speak|strong="G3004"\w* \w the|strong="G1537"\w* truth, \w why|strong="G5101"\w* \w do|strong="G5101"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*?
\v 47 \w The|strong="G1537"\w* \w one|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* hears \w God|strong="G2316"\w*'s \w words|strong="G4487"\w*; \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w why|strong="G1223"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w do|strong="G1510"\w* \nd \w not|strong="G3756"\w*\nd* hear, \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*.”\f + \fr 8:47 \ft Here is another plain statement.\f*
\p 
\v 48 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jews|strong="G2453"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w We|strong="G2249"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w a|strong="G2192"\w* \w Samaritan|strong="G4541"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w a|strong="G2192"\w* \w demon|strong="G1140"\w*\f + \fr 8:48 \ft A lot of people heard Jesus say that the leaders were not of God but of the devil. They did not want to swallow that in silence but they could not refute Him either, so they resort to ‘ad hominum’ argument.\f*—\w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w we|strong="G2249"\w* wrong?”
\v 49 \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* answered: “\bd \nd \w I|strong="G1473"\w*\nd*\bd* \w do|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w a|strong="G2192"\w* \w demon|strong="G1140"\w*; \w rather|strong="G3756"\w*, \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w honor|strong="G5091"\w* \w my|strong="G1473"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w*, \w while|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* dishonor \w me|strong="G1473"\w*.
\v 50 \w Yet|strong="G2532"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w do|strong="G2919"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w seek|strong="G2212"\w* \w my|strong="G2212"\w* \w glory|strong="G1391"\w*; \w there|strong="G2532"\w* \nd \w is|strong="G1510"\w*\nd* \w One|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w seeks|strong="G2212"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w judges|strong="G2919"\w*.
\v 51 Most assuredly \w I|strong="G1437"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, \w if|strong="G1437"\w* \w anyone|strong="G5100"\w* \w should|strong="G5100"\w* \w keep|strong="G5083"\w* \w my|strong="G1699"\w* \w word|strong="G3056"\w* \w he|strong="G3588"\w* \w will|strong="G5100"\w* \w never|strong="G3756"\w* \w ever|strong="G3756"\w* \w see|strong="G2334"\w* \w death|strong="G2288"\w*.”\f + \fr 8:51 \ft The Lord is unusually emphatic here. He is evidently referring to spiritual death, but the Jews took it as referring to physical death. Notice that He said “\nd keep\nd* my word”—again the emphasis is on commitment and obedience.\f*
\s2 “before Abraham was, I AM”
\p 
\v 52 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jews|strong="G2453"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w Now|strong="G3568"\w* \w we|strong="G1437"\w* \w know|strong="G1097"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w a|strong="G2192"\w* \w demon|strong="G1140"\w*! Abraham \w died|strong="G2288"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w so|strong="G2532"\w* \w did|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w prophets|strong="G4396"\w*; \w yet|strong="G2532"\w* \nd \w you|strong="G4771"\w*\nd* \w say|strong="G3004"\w*, ‘\w If|strong="G1437"\w* \w anyone|strong="G5100"\w* \w should|strong="G5100"\w* \w keep|strong="G5083"\w* \w my|strong="G5083"\w* \w word|strong="G3056"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w will|strong="G2532"\w* \w never|strong="G3756"\w* \w ever|strong="G3756"\w* \w taste|strong="G1089"\w* \w death|strong="G2288"\w*’!
\v 53 \w Surely|strong="G3361"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* aren'\w t|strong="G3588"\w* \w greater|strong="G3173"\w* \w than|strong="G3173"\w* \w our|strong="G2532"\w* \w father|strong="G3962"\w* Abraham, \w who|strong="G5101"\w* \w died|strong="G3588"\w*?\f + \fr 8:53 \ft Of course He was greater than Abraham, but they were wearing spiritual blinders.\f* \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w prophets|strong="G4396"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w dead|strong="G3173"\w*. \w Who|strong="G5101"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w make|strong="G4160"\w* \w yourself|strong="G4572"\w* \w out|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w*?”
\v 54 \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w*: “\w If|strong="G1437"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w glorify|strong="G1392"\w* \w myself|strong="G1683"\w*, \w my|strong="G1473"\w* \w glory|strong="G1391"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w nothing|strong="G3762"\w*. \w It|strong="G3754"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w my|strong="G1473"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w glorifies|strong="G1392"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*, \w of|strong="G2316"\w* \w whom|strong="G3739"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w*, ‘\w He|strong="G3739"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w our|strong="G2316"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*.’\f + \fr 8:54 \ft They have been refusing to understand repeated hints, so here Jesus makes a flat statement: His Father is God, Jehovah. Perhaps 30% of the Greek manuscripts have ‘your God’, making it an indirect quote.\f*
\v 55 \w Yet|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w known|strong="G1097"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w do|strong="G1492"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*. \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w if|strong="G2579"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w should|strong="G1492"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w do|strong="G1492"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w would|strong="G2532"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w liar|strong="G5583"\w* \w just|strong="G2532"\w* \w like|strong="G3664"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* (pl);\f + \fr 8:55 \ft Their father is a liar; they are liars. Rather than being conciliatory, Jesus is definitely aggressive. If any of them are to be saved they have to start on the basis of abject surrender.\f* \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w do|strong="G1492"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w keep|strong="G5083"\w* \w His|strong="G2532"\w* \w word|strong="G3056"\w*.
\v 56 \w Your|strong="G2532"\w* \w father|strong="G3962"\w* Abraham \w was|strong="G3588"\w* overjoyed \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w see|strong="G3708"\w* \w my|strong="G1699"\w* \w day|strong="G2250"\w*;\f + \fr 8:56 \ft What day was that? I suppose He is referring to the time that He, Jehovah the Son (the Angel of Jehovah), paid Abraham a personal visit. From the Record it is clear that Abraham knew very well that he was talking with Jehovah. Don't you know that was the high point in Abraham's life! Hey, just stop and think about what happened.\f* yes, \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w saw|strong="G1492"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w rejoiced|strong="G5463"\w*.”
\p 
\v 57 \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jews|strong="G2453"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w You|strong="G3708"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w not|strong="G3768"\w* \w yet|strong="G2532"\w* \w fifty|strong="G4004"\w* \w years|strong="G2094"\w* \w old|strong="G2094"\w*,\f + \fr 8:57 \ft This statement intrigues me. Jesus was thirty-three, and they had researched His past, so why did they say ‘fifty’? Could it be that Jesus looked older than He was? I wonder if the heavy pressures of His life style and ministry did not take a toll on His physical body, making Him prematurely gray, as it were.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G3708"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w seen|strong="G3708"\w* Abraham?!”
\v 58 \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w them|strong="G3004"\w*, “Most assuredly \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, \w before|strong="G4250"\w* Abraham \w came|strong="G1096"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w be|strong="G1096"\w*, \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w AM|strong="G1510"\w*!”\f + \fr 8:58 \ft Here Jesus is openly, unmistakably claiming to be Jehovah. They are obliged to get the point, and not wanting to acknowledge Him they pick up stones. At this point to argue, as some have done, that Jesus was merely a good, moral man won't wash. Either He was God, as He claimed; or He was a charlatan, a megalomaniac; or He was demonized. The Jews at that time took the third option; I take the first.\f*
\v 59 \w Then|strong="G3767"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* picked \w up|strong="G1909"\w* \w stones|strong="G3037"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* throw \w at|strong="G1909"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*;\f + \fr 8:59 \ft Since certain situations demanded a stoning, there were doubtless piles of ammunition placed strategically around the temple premises.\f* \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* \w concealed|strong="G2928"\w*\f + \fr 8:59 \ft The familiar “hid Himself” is not the best rendering here. Jesus did not try to hide behind a pillar, or whatever. Obviously they would have seen Him and started stoning. He became invisible and simply walked out, passing right through the middle of them. About half a percent of the Greek manuscripts, of objectively inferior quality, omit “going through the middle of them; yes, that's how He got away” (as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.). The 99.5% are doubtless correct, and supply an important detail.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w went|strong="G1831"\w* \w out|strong="G1831"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w temple|strong="G2413"\w*, \w going|strong="G2532"\w* \w through|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* middle \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*; \w yes|strong="G1161"\w*, \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w how|strong="G1161"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w got|strong="G1831"\w* \w away|strong="G1831"\w*!
\c 9
\s1 The man born blind
\m 
\v 1 \w Now|strong="G2532"\w* \w as|strong="G2532"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w was|strong="G2532"\w* \w passing|strong="G3855"\w* \w by|strong="G1537"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w saw|strong="G3708"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w man|strong="G5185"\w* \w blind|strong="G5185"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w birth|strong="G1079"\w*.
