\v 32 \w Since|strong="G3754"\w* time began \w it|strong="G3754"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* \w never|strong="G3756"\w* heard \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w anyone|strong="G5100"\w* opened \w the|strong="G1537"\w* \w eyes|strong="G3788"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w a|strong="G3756"\w* \w person|strong="G5100"\w* \w born|strong="G1080"\w* \w blind|strong="G5185"\w*.\f + \fr 9:32 \ft Jesus had already restored sight to many blind people, but evidently this was the first instance of giving sight to one \nd born\nd* blind, congenitally blind. No one challenged the man's statement. The man's argument here is very strong; irrefutable, in fact.\f*
\v 33 \w If|strong="G1487"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w man|strong="G3778"\w* \w were|strong="G1510"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w from|strong="G3844"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w he|strong="G3778"\w* \w would|strong="G2316"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* \w able|strong="G1410"\w* \w to|strong="G1410"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w* \w anything|strong="G3762"\w*.”
\v 34 \w They|strong="G2532"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w him|strong="G2532"\w*, “\w You|strong="G4771"\w* \w were|strong="G2532"\w* totally \w born|strong="G1080"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* sins, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w are|strong="G2532"\w* \w teaching|strong="G1321"\w* \nd \w us|strong="G3004"\w*\nd*?” \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w expelled|strong="G1544"\w* \w him|strong="G2532"\w*.\f + \fr 9:34 \ft The Pharisees here demonstrate their moral and intellectual bankruptcy. They couldn't answer the man, he had bested them fair and square, so they resort to the cowardly tactic of expelling him. (“Totally born in sins”—like the disciples, the Pharisees figured there was a lot of sin involved, for the man to be born blind.)\f*
\p 
\v 35 \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* heard \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w had|strong="G2424"\w* \w expelled|strong="G1544"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w finding|strong="G2147"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w Do|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w God|strong="G3004"\w*?”\f + \fr 9:35 \ft Less than 0.5% of the Greek manuscripts, of objectively inferior quality, read “Man” instead of “God” (as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.).\f*
\v 36 \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w answered|strong="G3004"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w*, “\w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w who|strong="G5101"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w*, \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w*, \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w I|strong="G2532"\w* \w may|strong="G2532"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w Him|strong="G1565"\w*?”
\v 37 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w You|strong="G4771"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w both|strong="G2532"\w* \w seen|strong="G3708"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w One|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w speaking|strong="G2980"\w* \w with|strong="G3326"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w*.”
\v 38 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G5346"\w*, “\w Lord|strong="G2962"\w*, \w I|strong="G2532"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w*!” \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w worshiped|strong="G4352"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*.
\v 39 \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w*, “\w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w came|strong="G2064"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w world|strong="G2889"\w* \w for|strong="G1519"\w* \w judgment|strong="G2917"\w*, \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w do|strong="G1096"\w* \w not|strong="G3361"\w* see \w may|strong="G2532"\w* see, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* ‘see’ \w may|strong="G2532"\w* \w become|strong="G1096"\w* \w blind|strong="G5185"\w*.”\f + \fr 9:39 \ft In verse 5 of this chapter Jesus declared Himself to be “the Light of the world”. Light enables people to see—“so that those who do not see may see”. But too much light blinds—“and those who ‘see’ may become blind”. The Pharisees had ‘spies’ dogging Jesus wherever He went, and they speak up in the next verse (40). Romans 2:17-20 explains their attitude:\fp Look, you declare yourself a \nd Jew\nd*, and rest on the Law, and boast in God, \fv 18\ft and know the Will, and approve the superior things, being instructed out of the Law. \fv 19\ft Further, you are confident that you yourself are a guide to the blind, a light to those in darkness, \fv 20\ft an instructor of the foolish, a teacher of the immature, having in the Law the embodiment of knowledge and truth. [“The embodiment of knowledge and truth” is an excellent description of the Scriptures.]\fp The light of the Law enabled them to see, up to a point, but the Light that Jesus offered blinded them, since they did not want to acknowledge it.\f*
\p 
\v 40 \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w some|strong="G3588"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Pharisees|strong="G5330"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w were|strong="G1510"\w* \w with|strong="G3326"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* heard \w these|strong="G3326"\w* \w words|strong="G2532"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\nd \w We|strong="G2249"\w*\nd* aren'\w t|strong="G3588"\w* \w blind|strong="G5185"\w* \w too|strong="G2532"\w*, \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w we|strong="G2249"\w*?”
\v 41 \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w If|strong="G1487"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w were|strong="G1510"\w* ‘\w blind|strong="G5185"\w*’ \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w would|strong="G1510"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* sin. \w But|strong="G1161"\w* \w now|strong="G1161"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w*, ‘\w We|strong="G3754"\w* see,’ \w so|strong="G1161"\w* \w your|strong="G2192"\w* sin \w remains|strong="G3306"\w*.\f + \fr 9:41 \ft According to Romans 5:13, “sin is not imputed where there is no law”, because it is the Law that defines what sin is (Romans 3:20). So those who are without the light of the Law are ‘blind’ in that sense, and their sin is not imputed. In contrast, the Pharisees prided themselves on having the light of the Law, to the point of being guides to the blind, but since they themselves did not obey the Law, their sin remained.\f*
\c 10
\s1 Jesus the Shepherd
\s2 A true shepherd
\m 
\v 1 “Most assuredly \w I|strong="G2532"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w does|strong="G1510"\w* \w not|strong="G3361"\w* \w enter|strong="G1525"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* sheepfold \w by|strong="G1223"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w door|strong="G2374"\w*, \w but|strong="G2532"\w* climbs \w up|strong="G1519"\w* \w some|strong="G3588"\w* \w other|strong="G3361"\w* \w way|strong="G1223"\w*, \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w same|strong="G1565"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w thief|strong="G2812"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w robber|strong="G3027"\w*.
\v 2 \w But|strong="G1161"\w* \w he|strong="G1161"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w enters|strong="G1525"\w* \w by|strong="G1223"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w door|strong="G2374"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w a|strong="G1510"\w* \w shepherd|strong="G4166"\w*\f + \fr 10:2 \ft “\nd A\nd* shepherd”—the fold was communal, so the sheep belonged to a variety of shepherds. That is why each one had to call his own sheep by name (verse 3). The doorkeeper would know all the shepherds.\f* \w of|strong="G1223"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w sheep|strong="G4263"\w*.
\v 3 \w To|strong="G2532"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w doorkeeper|strong="G2377"\w* opens, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w sheep|strong="G4263"\w* \w hear|strong="G5456"\w* \w his|strong="G2398"\w* \w voice|strong="G5456"\w*; \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w calls|strong="G5455"\w* \w his|strong="G2398"\w* \w own|strong="G2398"\w* \w sheep|strong="G4263"\w* \w by|strong="G2596"\w* \w name|strong="G3686"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w leads|strong="G1806"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w* \w out|strong="G1806"\w*.
\v 4 \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w whenever|strong="G3752"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* takes \w out|strong="G1544"\w* \w his|strong="G3956"\w* \w own|strong="G2398"\w* \w sheep|strong="G4263"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w goes|strong="G4198"\w* \w ahead|strong="G1715"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*,\f + \fr 10:4 \ft He ‘leads’, not ‘drives’. Going out they need to be led; only the shepherd knows where they are going.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w sheep|strong="G4263"\w* \w follow|strong="G4198"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w his|strong="G3956"\w* \w voice|strong="G5456"\w*.
\v 5 \w But|strong="G1161"\w* \w they|strong="G1161"\w* \w will|strong="G3748"\w* \nd \w not|strong="G3756"\w*\nd* \w follow|strong="G1161"\w* \w a|strong="G1161"\w* stranger; \w rather|strong="G3756"\w* \w they|strong="G1161"\w* \w will|strong="G3748"\w* run \w away|strong="G5343"\w* \w from|strong="G5456"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w they|strong="G1161"\w* \w do|strong="G1492"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w voice|strong="G5456"\w* \w of|strong="G5456"\w* strangers.”
\v 6 \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w gave|strong="G3588"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* illustration, \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w they|strong="G1161"\w* \w did|strong="G1097"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w understand|strong="G1097"\w* \w what|strong="G5101"\w* \w He|strong="G1161"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w telling|strong="G3004"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*.
\s2 The Door
\p 
\v 7 \w Then|strong="G3767"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* addressed \w them|strong="G3588"\w* \w again|strong="G3825"\w*: “Most assuredly \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w door|strong="G2374"\w* \w of|strong="G2424"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w sheep|strong="G4263"\w*.
\v 8 \w All|strong="G3956"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w ever|strong="G3745"\w* \w came|strong="G2064"\w* \w before|strong="G4253"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w thieves|strong="G2812"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w robbers|strong="G3027"\w*,\f + \fr 10:8 \ft Although some 50% of the Greek manuscripts (also the three ancient versions) omit “before me”, we are virtually obliged to understand this, in any case, since presumably Jesus means pretending to be the Messiah. Gamaliel refers to two possible candidates in Acts 5:36-37.\f* \w but|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w sheep|strong="G4263"\w* \w did|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* listen \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*.\f + \fr 10:8 \ft Any true servants of God, such as Simeon and Anna (Luke 2:25-38), would not be taken in by an imposter.\f*
\v 9 \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w door|strong="G2374"\w*. \w If|strong="G1437"\w* \w anyone|strong="G5100"\w* \w enters|strong="G1525"\w* \nd \w by|strong="G1223"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*\nd*, \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* \w saved|strong="G4982"\w*,\f + \fr 10:9 \ft Jesus is \nd the\nd* doorway, the only means of access into eternal life, a truth He will emphasize again in John 14:6.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* \w go|strong="G1831"\w* \w in|strong="G1525"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w out|strong="G1831"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w find|strong="G2147"\w* \w pasture|strong="G3542"\w*.\f + \fr 10:9 \ft What does a sheep want? Protection and pasture. These Jesus offers, but since people are more complex than sheep, He offers abundant life.\f*
\v 10 \w The|strong="G2532"\w* \w thief|strong="G2812"\w* \w comes|strong="G2064"\w* \w only|strong="G1487"\w* \w in|strong="G2532"\w* \w order|strong="G2443"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w steal|strong="G2813"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w kill|strong="G2380"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* destroy.\f + \fr 10:10 \ft The original thief is Satan. “The thief comes” VS “I have come”—since Jesus contrasts “the thief” with Himself, that thief is presumably Satan. Jesus calls him a murderer and a liar in John 8:44. A thief is usually a liar as well, and vice versa.\f* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w come|strong="G2064"\w* \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w may|strong="G2532"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w life|strong="G2222"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w abundantly|strong="G4053"\w*.
\s2 The Good Shepherd
\p 
\v 11 “\w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w good|strong="G2570"\w* \w shepherd|strong="G4166"\w*.\f + \fr 10:11 \ft Here Jesus changes the figure—as \nd the\nd* good shepherd He really cares about the sheep, to the point of dying for them.\f* \w The|strong="G3588"\w* \w good|strong="G2570"\w* \w shepherd|strong="G4166"\w* \w lays|strong="G5087"\w* \w down|strong="G5087"\w* \w his|strong="G5087"\w* \w life|strong="G5590"\w* \w on|strong="G5228"\w* \w behalf|strong="G5228"\w* \w of|strong="G5228"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w sheep|strong="G4263"\w*.
\v 12 \w But|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w hired|strong="G3411"\w* \w man|strong="G3739"\w*, \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w being|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w shepherd|strong="G4166"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* owning \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w sheep|strong="G4263"\w*, \w sees|strong="G2334"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w wolf|strong="G3074"\w* \w coming|strong="G2064"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* abandons \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w sheep|strong="G4263"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* runs \w away|strong="G5343"\w*; \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w wolf|strong="G3074"\w* snatches \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w sheep|strong="G4263"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w scatters|strong="G4650"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*.
