\p 
\v 17 \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w when|strong="G1722"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w had|strong="G2192"\w* \w come|strong="G2064"\w*, \w He|strong="G3588"\w* \w found|strong="G2147"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w he|strong="G3588"\w* \w had|strong="G2192"\w* \w already|strong="G2235"\w* \w been|strong="G2192"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w tomb|strong="G3419"\w* \w four|strong="G5064"\w* \w days|strong="G2250"\w*.\f + \fr 11:17 \ft Four days—that seems like quite a bit. In verses 11 and 14 Jesus makes clear that Lazarus had died before He left Perea. Someone in a hurry could make the distance in one day. I can't prove it, but I imagine that the events recorded in Luke 18:18-19:27 (and the parallel passages in Matthew and Mark) occurred between verses 16 & 17, here. Jesus probably spent a night at Zacchaeus' house (see Luke 19:5), doing the climb (of over 3,000 vertical feet) from Jericho to Jerusalem the next morning. The Lord deliberately took His time, delayed His arrival.\f*
\v 18 (\w Now|strong="G1161"\w* Bethany \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w near|strong="G1451"\w* \w Jerusalem|strong="G2414"\w*, \w about|strong="G5613"\w* \w two|strong="G5613"\w* \w miles|strong="G4712"\w* away,
